            {
              "id": "2fabb73c-9526-3eec-9f89-413de89bd715",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior. This vulnerability occurs when a pointer to a loop iteration variable is stored, leading to the same memory address being used for each iteration. This can result in the same value being used for all iterations, which is typically not the intended behavior.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the variable `b` is a pointer to the current `roleBinding` in the `roleBindings` slice. The `b` pointer is then appended to the `bindingMap` slice. However, because `b` is a pointer, all entries in `bindingMap` will point to the last `roleBinding` in `roleBindings` after the loop finishes.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid storing pointers to loop iteration variables. Instead, you should create a new variable within the loop scope and store a pointer to that variable.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nfor _, b := range roleBindings {\n    bCopy := b\n    bindingMap[b.Namespace] = append(bindingMap[b.Namespace], &bCopy)\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a copy of `b` is created for each iteration of the loop. This ensures that each entry in `bindingMap` points to a unique `roleBinding`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not specify any library dependencies. However, the types of `roleBindings` and `bindingMap` are not defined. Depending on the definitions of these types, additional library dependencies may be required.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
