            {
              "id": "b214f2fa-9112-3696-88f2-5dda9430a7ae",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability due to Modification of `shapeResponse` Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided has a potential nil dereference vulnerability. This occurs when the `computeClient.ListImages` function call fails and returns an error. In this case, the `shapeResponse` variable is likely to be `nil`. However, the error handling code attempts to access `shapeResponse.RawResponse`, which would result in a nil dereference panic if `shapeResponse` is `nil`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always check if a variable is `nil` before attempting to access its fields or methods. This is especially important when dealing with return values from functions that can fail and return `nil` values.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\nshapeResponse, err := computeClient.ListImages(context.Background(), imageRequest)\nif err != nil {\n\tlogrus.Debugf(\"[oci-handler] error listing images with Compute client: %v\", err)\n\tif shapeResponse != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, getErrorCode(shapeResponse.RawResponse), err\n\t}\n\treturn nil, nil, err\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we add an additional check for `shapeResponse != nil` before attempting to access `shapeResponse.RawResponse`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet appears to require the following libraries:\n\n- A library for the `computeClient` object, which is likely a part of an OCI SDK.\n- The `context` package from the standard library.\n- The `logrus` package for logging.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A2:2017 Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
