            {
              "id": "340fc301-c5fd-3c66-bfe5-7bbedc98391b",
              "name": "\"Host Key Verification Disabled, Allowing Man-in-the-Middle Attacks\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Host Key Verification Disabled, Allowing Man-in-the-Middle Attacks\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a situation where the SSH client is configured to ignore the host key verification process. This can potentially allow a man-in-the-middle (MITM) attack, where an attacker intercepts and possibly alters the communication between two parties who believe they are directly communicating with each other.\n\nIn the provided code sink, `HostKeyCallback: ssh.InsecureIgnoreHostKey()`, the `ssh.InsecureIgnoreHostKey()` function is used, which means the client does not verify the server's host key, making it vulnerable to MITM attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, the host key of the server should be verified during the SSH handshake. This can be done by using the `ssh.FixedHostKey()` function, which requires the host key of the server. If the server's host key is not known in advance, a callback function can be used to check the host key against a list of trusted keys.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `ssh.InsecureIgnoreHostKey()`, use `ssh.FixedHostKey()` or a custom callback function. Here is an example of how to use `ssh.FixedHostKey()`:\n\n```go\npublicKey, _, _, _, err := ssh.ParseAuthorizedKey([]byte(publicKeyString))\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatalf(\"Failed to parse public key: %v\", err)\n}\n\nconfig := &ssh.ClientConfig{\n    User: \"username\",\n    Auth: []ssh.AuthMethod{\n        ssh.Password(\"password\"),\n    },\n    HostKeyCallback: ssh.FixedHostKey(publicKey),\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `publicKeyString` should be replaced with the actual public key of the server.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- golang.org/x/crypto/ssh\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Configuration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n- [CWE-295: Improper Certificate Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-295",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-295"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8873bb9f-24a7-3545-b120-1f2c85c89feb",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is shared among multiple goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines will see the last value of the loop variable. In the provided code, the `testCase` variable is shared among multiple test cases in the `t.Run` function, which can lead to unexpected behavior if the test cases are run in parallel.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables among multiple goroutines. Instead, you should create a new variable within the scope of the goroutine and use that instead.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, testCase := range testCases {\n    testCase := testCase // Fix: create a new variable within the scope of the goroutine\n    t.Run(testCase.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        ctrl := gomock.NewController(t)\n        defer ctrl.Finish()\n\n        cache := testCase.setup(ctrl)\n        s := &Store{\n            Store:            &testCase.inner,\n            ProvClusterCache: cache,\n        }\n\n        resp, err := s.Delete(nil, nil, credID)\n\n        if testCase.expected.wantAPIError != nil {\n            require.Error(t, err)\n            var apiErr *httperror.APIError\n            require.True(t, errors.As(err, &apiErr), \"expected httperror.APIError, got %T\", err)\n            assert.Equal(t, testCase.expected.wantAPIError.Code.Status, apiErr.Code.Status)\n            assert.False(t, testCase.inner.deleteCalled, \"inner store should not be called on deny/error\")\n            return\n        }\n\n        require.NoError(t, err)\n        assert.True(t, testCase.inner.deleteCalled, \"inner store should be called\")\n        assert.Equal(t, testCase.expected.wantResp, resp)\n    })\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `github.com/golang/mock/gomock`\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/require`\n- `net/http`\n\n## References\n\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE-567)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/567.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-567",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/567.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-567"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "5baf78b3-2f9f-3880-a84e-e4188d774ecb",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if the data written directly to the `http.ResponseWriter` is not properly sanitized or escaped, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS attacks occur when an attacker injects malicious scripts into content that is served to other users. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including session hijacking, identity theft, defacement of websites, and other malicious activities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape any user-supplied input before writing it to the `http.ResponseWriter`. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package, which automatically escapes any data that is rendered in a template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing serialized data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, use the `html/template` package to safely render data in a template. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"html/template\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    tmpl, err := template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n\n    data := getData() // This function should return the data to be rendered in the template.\n\n    err = tmpl.Execute(w, data)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")` line creates a new template that will render the data. The `tmpl.Execute(w, data)` line then writes the data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, automatically escaping any potentially harmful content.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "805dc39b-9118-38c0-85fb-62bbd31ac737",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if the data written directly to the `http.ResponseWriter` is not properly sanitized or escaped, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS attacks occur when an attacker injects malicious scripts into content that is served to other users. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including session hijacking, identity theft, defacement of websites, and other malicious activities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape any user-supplied input before writing it to the `http.ResponseWriter`. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package, which automatically escapes any data that is rendered in a template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing serialized data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, use the `html/template` package to safely render data in a template. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"html/template\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    tmpl, err := template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n\n    data := getData() // This function should return the data to be rendered in the template.\n\n    err = tmpl.Execute(w, data)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")` line creates a new template that will render the data. The `tmpl.Execute(w, data)` line then writes the data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, automatically escaping any potentially harmful content.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
