            {
              "id": "b4954360-fd34-3b03-9892-6e5ff00a10ce",
              "name": "HTTP WebSocket handshake Origin header vulnerability to Cross Site Request Forgery (CSRF) due to unverified origin domain.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe HTTP WebSocket handshake Origin header vulnerability to Cross Site Request Forgery (CSRF) due to unverified origin domain is a security flaw that can occur in Go programming language when the origin of a WebSocket handshake request is not properly verified. This can allow an attacker to send malicious requests from a user's browser to the server, potentially leading to unauthorized actions being performed on the user's behalf.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always verify the origin of a WebSocket handshake request. This can be done by checking the `Origin` header of the request and comparing it to a list of trusted domains. If the origin is not in the list of trusted domains, the server should reject the request.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to verify the origin of a WebSocket handshake request in Go:\n\n```go\nupgrader := websocket.Upgrader{\n    CheckOrigin: func(r *http.Request) bool {\n        // Check if the Origin header is in the list of trusted domains\n        return r.Header.Get(\"Origin\") == \"http://trusteddomain.com\"\n    },\n}\n\nconn, err := upgrader.Upgrade(w, req, nil)\nif err != nil {\n    // Handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `CheckOrigin` function is used to verify the origin of the request. If the origin is not `http://trusteddomain.com`, the request is rejected.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `github.com/gorilla/websocket`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
