              "id": "87668077-015d-3263-b591-066085727f14",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if the data written directly to the `http.ResponseWriter` is not properly sanitized or escaped, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS attacks occur when an attacker injects malicious scripts into content that is served to other users. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including session hijacking, identity theft, defacement of websites, and other malicious activities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape any user-supplied input before writing it to the `http.ResponseWriter`. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package, which automatically escapes any data that is rendered in a template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing serialized data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, use the `html/template` package to safely render data in a template. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"html/template\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    tmpl, err := template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n\n    data := getData() // This function should return the data to be rendered in the template.\n\n    err = tmpl.Execute(w, data)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")` line creates a new template that will render the data. The `tmpl.Execute(w, data)` line then writes the data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, automatically escaping any potentially harmful content.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
