            {
              "id": "603f40f1-f6f6-3a88-bf1a-03555e9d887f",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" vulnerability refers to the situation where a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` field of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `isSecure`, which might be `false` depending on the context. If `Secure` is `false`, the cookie can be transmitted over unencrypted connections, which makes it vulnerable to interception and theft.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` field to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which encrypts the data and prevents it from being easily intercepted.\n\nAlso, consider setting the `SameSite` attribute to `Strict` or `Lax` to prevent the cookie from being sent in cross-site requests, which can help protect against cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     cookieName,\n\tValue:    \"\",\n\tSecure:   true, // Always secure\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tMaxAge:   -1,\n\tExpires:  cookieUnsetTimestamp,\n\tSameSite: http.SameSiteStrictMode, // Prevents the cookie from being sent in cross-site requests\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code depends on the `net/http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [OWASP - SameSite](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#samesite-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "5e8d68ee-ff4e-3850-95d1-2817d4673621",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior and potential security vulnerabilities. This happens when a pointer to a loop variable is shared across multiple goroutines. Since the loop variable is reused across iterations, all goroutines might end up seeing the last value of the loop variable.\n\nIn the provided code, there is no such vulnerability as there are no goroutines involved and no pointers to loop variables are being shared.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables across goroutines. If you need to share data, create a new variable within the scope of the loop and share a pointer to that variable.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nAs mentioned, the provided code does not exhibit this vulnerability. However, if it did, the fix would look something like this:\n\n```go\nfor _, rule := range gr.Rules {\n    rule := rule // create a new variable within the scope of the loop\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to depend on a custom `slice` package that is not part of the standard Go library. The `slice` package should provide the `ContainsString` function. The `gr.Rules` suggests that `gr` is an instance of a custom struct that has a `Rules` field.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-118: Incorrect Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n\nPlease note that the CWE link does not directly correspond to the vulnerability discussed, as there is no specific CWE for \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\". The linked CWE is the closest match discussing issues with incorrect access of indexable resources."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-118",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-118"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ce237bf7-82f9-3aa0-8176-e5d1087640dd",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if the data written directly to the `http.ResponseWriter` is not properly sanitized or escaped, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS attacks occur when an attacker injects malicious scripts into content that is served to other users. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including session hijacking, identity theft, defacement of websites, and other malicious activities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape any user-supplied input before writing it to the `http.ResponseWriter`. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package, which automatically escapes any data that is rendered in a template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing serialized data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, use the `html/template` package to safely render data in a template. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"html/template\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    tmpl, err := template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n\n    data := getData() // This function should return the data to be rendered in the template.\n\n    err = tmpl.Execute(w, data)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")` line creates a new template that will render the data. The `tmpl.Execute(w, data)` line then writes the data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, automatically escaping any potentially harmful content.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
