            {
              "id": "bcc06214-36d9-395e-af39-e45cec3622ba",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a developer uses the address of a loop iterator variable in Go. This can lead to unexpected behavior because the address of the loop iterator variable is reused for each iteration of the loop, so each iteration ends up sharing the same variable. This can lead to bugs that are hard to detect and debug.\n\nIn the provided code, the variable `u` is a loop iterator variable and its address is being taken inside the loop and assigned to the `match` variable. This can lead to unexpected behavior if the `match` variable is used outside the loop after the loop has finished executing.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, you should avoid taking the address of a loop iterator variable. Instead, you can use the index to access the slice element and take its address.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nfor i := range usersList.Items {\n    u := &usersList.Items[i]\n    if slice.ContainsString(u.PrincipalIDs, userPrincipalID) {\n        if match != nil {\n            // error out on duplicates\n            return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"can't find unique user for principal %v\", userPrincipalID)\n        }\n        match = u\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `fmt`: Standard library package for formatted I/O with functions analogous to C's printf and scanf.\n- `slice`: This is not a standard library and its implementation is not provided. It's assumed to be a custom package with a function `ContainsString`.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-118: Incorrect Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-118",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
