            {
              "id": "be2f6ca4-d9fc-3c2c-aae0-1a6de270593c",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if the data written directly to the `http.ResponseWriter` is not properly sanitized or escaped, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS attacks occur when an attacker injects malicious scripts into content that is served to other users. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including session hijacking, identity theft, defacement of websites, and other malicious activities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape any user-supplied input before writing it to the `http.ResponseWriter`. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package, which automatically escapes any data that is rendered in a template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing serialized data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, use the `html/template` package to safely render data in a template. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"html/template\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    tmpl, err := template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n\n    data := getData() // This function should return the data to be rendered in the template.\n\n    err = tmpl.Execute(w, data)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")` line creates a new template that will render the data. The `tmpl.Execute(w, data)` line then writes the data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, automatically escaping any potentially harmful content.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "dd9e7014-675b-3087-bd28-450171d4e1a4",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the user input will be executed by the browser.\n\nThis vulnerability is particularly dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser or system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes all data when rendering HTML templates.\n\nAdditionally, you should implement a Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict the sources from which scripts can be loaded. This can help to prevent the execution of injected scripts, even if an XSS vulnerability is present.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the user input to the HTTP response, you should use an HTML template to render the response. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"user\").Parse(\"<h1>{{.}}</h1>\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, searchUsersUser)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `{{.}}` placeholder in the template is automatically replaced with the value of `searchUsersUser`, and any HTML or JavaScript code in `searchUsersUser` is automatically escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go, so no additional installation is required.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e13a4259-b60f-3825-ba53-cec58c42e46c",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if the data written directly to the `http.ResponseWriter` is not properly sanitized or escaped, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS attacks occur when an attacker injects malicious scripts into content that is served to other users. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including session hijacking, identity theft, defacement of websites, and other malicious activities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape any user-supplied input before writing it to the `http.ResponseWriter`. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package, which automatically escapes any data that is rendered in a template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing serialized data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, use the `html/template` package to safely render data in a template. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"html/template\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    tmpl, err := template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n\n    data := getData() // This function should return the data to be rendered in the template.\n\n    err = tmpl.Execute(w, data)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")` line creates a new template that will render the data. The `tmpl.Execute(w, data)` line then writes the data to the `http.ResponseWriter`, automatically escaping any potentially harmful content.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
