            {
              "id": "9480afa7-9f58-3fe7-9533-c914dbb090a7",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a developer uses the address of a loop variable inside a goroutine. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines will share the same instance of the loop variable, which can be updated by any goroutine. This can lead to race conditions and data corruption.\n\nIn the provided code, there is no such vulnerability present. The code is not using goroutines or pointers in a way that would lead to this vulnerability. The code is simply iterating over `shapeResponse.Items` and checking if the `DisplayName` of each item contains certain strings.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, developers should be careful when using the address of a loop variable inside a goroutine. Instead of directly using the address of the loop variable, developers should create a new variable inside the loop and use its address instead.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nAs mentioned above, the provided code does not contain this vulnerability. However, if it did, the fix would look something like this:\n\n```go\nfor _, item := range shapeResponse.Items {\n    item := item // create a new variable\n    if !strings.Contains(*item.DisplayName, \"GPU\") &&\n        !strings.Contains(*item.DisplayName, \"Oracle-Linux-6\") &&\n        strings.Contains(*item.DisplayName, \"Oracle-Linux\") &&\n        !listContains(nodeImages, *(item.DisplayName)) {\n        nodeImages = append(nodeImages, *(item.DisplayName))\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `strings`: This is a standard library in Go, used for string manipulation.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-118: Improper Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n\nPlease note that the CWE link does not directly match the described vulnerability, as there is no specific CWE for \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\". The closest match is a range error, which can be a result of this vulnerability."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
