            {
              "id": "dddb1211-d563-3474-9a49-07121837e16e",
              "name": "Potential Logic Bug due to Variable 'err' Assigned from Two Different Sources",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Potential Logic Bug due to Variable 'err' Assigned from Two Different Sources\" in Go programming language arises when a variable, in this case 'err', is assigned from two different sources. This can lead to confusion and unexpected behavior as the variable 'err' may not contain the value expected at a certain point in the code. This can lead to bugs that are hard to detect and fix.\n\nIn the provided code, 'err' is assigned a value from the function `access.ByID()` and later from the function `v.provClusterCache.GetByIndex()`. If the first function fails, the error is handled and then 'err' is assigned a new value from the second function. If the second function also fails, the error is returned. However, if the first function fails with a specific error and the second function succeeds, the original error is lost and not handled properly.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use separate error variables for different function calls. This ensures that each error is handled properly and independently of others. It also makes the code easier to understand and debug.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```go\nif err1 := access.ByID(apiContext, &schema.Version, client.CloudCredentialType, id, &client.CloudCredentialClient{}); err1 != nil {\n\tif apiError, ok := err1.(*httperror.APIError); ok {\n\t\tif apiError.Code.Status == httperror.PermissionDenied.Status || apiError.Code.Status == httperror.NotFound.Status {\n\t\t\tvar clusters []*prov.Cluster\n\t\t\tclusters, err2 := v.provClusterCache.GetByIndex(provcluster.ByCloudCred, id)\n\t\t\tif err2 != nil || len(clusters) == 0 {\n\t\t\t\treturn nil, httperror.NotFound, fmt.Errorf(\"cloud credential not found\")\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\tfor _, cluster := range clusters {\n\t\t\t\tif err3 := access.ByID(apiContext, &schema.Version, client.ClusterType, cluster.Status.ClusterName, &client.Cluster{}); err3 == nil {\n\t\t\t\t\tbreak\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\tif err1 != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, httperror.NotFound, err1\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- `access`\n- `apiContext`\n- `schema`\n- `client`\n- `httperror`\n- `prov`\n- `provcluster`\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE for Improper Handling of Errors](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/391.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c21ee62a-9783-3154-8cbc-9f13338e6f4e",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detection in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` method is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, this method does not perform HTML escaping, which can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities if user-controlled data is directly written to the response without proper sanitization. XSS attacks can allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users, leading to a variety of potential security issues such as stealing user data, performing actions on behalf of the user, or exploiting the user's system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done by using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes HTML content. Additionally, it is also recommended to set the HTTP response header `Content-Type` to `text/html; charset=utf-8` to ensure that the browser interprets the response as HTML.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user-controlled data to the HTTP response, use the `html/template` package to safely render the data:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"safe\").Parse(`{{.}}`)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(res, js)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `js` is the user-controlled data. The `template.Execute()` method automatically escapes any HTML content in `js`, preventing XSS attacks.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "98a93c45-0dd5-3fcd-9bf4-b3bf35d56405",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform any HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the user input will be executed by the browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data that is embedded in the HTML template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to fix the vulnerability in the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"someTemplate\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, buf)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `template.Execute()` function is used instead of `http.ResponseWriter.write()`. This function automatically escapes any data that is embedded in the HTML template.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go, so no additional installation is required.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1ccb1a1e-545c-3e34-b082-b4eceb865cb6",
              "name": "User-Input Crafted HTTP Redirect Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"User-Input Crafted HTTP Redirect Vulnerability Detected\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when an application accepts user-controlled input that specifies a link to an external site, and uses that link in a Redirect call. This could allow an attacker to craft a malicious URL that redirects users to a malicious site, leading to phishing attacks, session theft, or forcing the user to perform unwanted actions.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when using the `http.Redirect` function with a user-controlled input as the URL to redirect to.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to validate user input before using it in a redirect function. This can be done by checking if the URL belongs to a list of trusted URLs, or by verifying that the URL does not lead to an external site.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple way to validate the URL before redirecting:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"net/url\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    redirectURL := r.URL.Query().Get(\"redirectURL\")\n    parsedURL, err := url.Parse(redirectURL)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, \"Invalid URL\", http.StatusBadRequest)\n        return\n    }\n    if parsedURL.Host != \"\" && parsedURL.Host != r.Host {\n        http.Error(w, \"External redirects not allowed\", http.StatusForbidden)\n        return\n    }\n    http.Redirect(w, r, redirectURL, http.StatusFound)\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, we parse the URL and check if the host is either empty (meaning it's a relative URL) or the same as the request's host. If it's not, we return an error instead of redirecting.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following standard library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`\n- `net/url`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-601"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6d3e8459-9016-378b-ae34-db3dd8a427b3",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability in `group` Variable Modification",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability in the `group` variable modification. This vulnerability occurs when the `group` variable is `nil` and the program tries to access its `Name` property. If `group` is `nil`, the program will panic and crash, leading to a denial of service.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always check if a variable is `nil` before trying to access its properties or methods. This can be done by adding an additional condition in the `if` statement to check if `group` is `nil`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\ngroup, err = s.groups.Update(group)\nif err != nil || group == nil {\n    if group == nil {\n        logrus.Error(\"scim::PatchGroup: group is nil\")\n    } else {\n        logrus.Errorf(\"scim::PatchGroup: failed to update group: %s\", err)\n    }\n    writeError(w, NewInternalError())\n    return\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we added a check for `group == nil` in the `if` statement. If `group` is `nil`, we log an error message and return.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet provided requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `logrus` package for logging errors.\n- The `s.groups.Update` method, which is likely part of a custom package.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
