            {
              "id": "aa0ae53b-8ec1-34f8-b252-73a0ecd52771",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detection in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, this function does not perform HTML escaping, which can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities if the data being written includes user-supplied input. XSS attacks occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always escape user-supplied input before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes all data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the response message to the `http.ResponseWriter`, you should use an `html/template` to render the response. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"response\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, d.ResponseMessage)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.New(\"response\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")` line creates a new HTML template that includes the response message. The `t.Execute(w, d.ResponseMessage)` line then renders this template to the `http.ResponseWriter`, automatically escaping the response message.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "dba31318-08a5-3e6f-a449-61b828e58780",
              "name": "Use of `interface{}` for deserialization can lead to security vulnerabilities (CWE-502); use a concrete struct type.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, using `interface{}` for deserialization can lead to security vulnerabilities (CWE-502). This is because the `interface{}` type in Go can hold any type, which can lead to unexpected behavior if the input is not properly validated or sanitized. An attacker could potentially exploit this to execute arbitrary code or cause a denial of service.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a concrete struct type instead of `interface{}` for deserialization. This ensures that the input is of a specific type and prevents unexpected behavior.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```go\nvar result interface{}\nerr := json.Unmarshal([]byte(annoValue), &result)\n```\n\nUse a concrete struct type:\n\n```go\ntype MyStruct struct {\n    Field1 string\n    Field2 int\n    // other fields...\n}\n\nvar result MyStruct\nerr := json.Unmarshal([]byte(annoValue), &result)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `encoding/json` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A8-Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A8_2017-Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-502",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-502"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "378a9af5-53df-3a5c-afb3-deb414565a80",
              "name": "Potential Dual Source Read Vulnerability in PAYGChartName Attribute",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential dual source read vulnerability in the `PAYGChartName` attribute. This vulnerability arises when a program reads input data from two different sources in a way that the data from the first source can influence the reading of the second source, and the program does not properly manage the two sources. In this case, the `usePAYG` query parameter is read from the request URL and used to determine the `cspChartName` and `cspChartNamespace` values. An attacker could potentially manipulate the `usePAYG` parameter to influence the program's behavior.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to validate and sanitize all input data. In this case, the `usePAYG` parameter should be validated to ensure it only contains expected values before it is used to determine the `cspChartName` and `cspChartNamespace` values. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```go\nusePAYG := request.URL.Query()[\"usePAYG\"]\nif len(usePAYG) > 0 {\n    if usePAYG[0] != \"true\" && usePAYG[0] != \"false\" {\n        // Handle invalid usePAYG value\n        return\n    }\n    if usePAYG[0] == \"true\" {\n        cspChartNamespace = cspadapter.PAYGChartNamespace\n        cspChartName = cspadapter.PAYGChartName\n    } else {\n        cspChartNamespace = cspadapter.MLOChartNamespace\n        cspChartName = cspadapter.MLOChartName\n    }\n    if !h.checkAuthorization(cspChartNamespace, cspMeteringArchiveConfigmap, writer, request) {\n        return\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet does not provide enough context to determine all library dependencies. However, it is clear that the `net/http` package from the Go standard library is used.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10-2017 A1-Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n- [CWE-20: Improper Input Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-20",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-20"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "170a4c20-0ed0-3a4b-a745-184dd4f1e20a",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability in `cluster` Variable Modification",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability. This occurs when the `cluster` variable is `nil` and the program tries to access `cluster.Name`. If `cluster` is `nil`, the program will panic and crash, leading to a denial of service.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this issue, you should always check if a variable is `nil` before trying to access its fields or methods. This is especially important when dealing with pointers, interfaces, or other types that can be `nil`.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\ncluster, err = p.Clusters.Update(cluster)\nif err != nil {\n    clusterName := \"\"\n    if cluster != nil {\n        clusterName = cluster.Name\n    }\n    return cluster, fmt.Errorf(\"[reconcileCluster] Failed to update cluster [%s]: %v\", clusterName, err)\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we first check if `cluster` is `nil` before trying to access `cluster.Name`. If `cluster` is `nil`, we use an empty string as the cluster name.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it seems to be using a custom package `p.Clusters` which would need to be imported. The `fmt` package is also used, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A2:2017 Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
