            {
              "id": "294b8d7d-521a-3698-8b8f-7ee4418823cc",
              "name": "Insecure gRPC Server Vulnerability due to Lack of Encryption and Credentials",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure gRPC Server Vulnerability due to Lack of Encryption and Credentials is a security vulnerability that occurs when a gRPC server is created without any form of encryption or credentials. This leaves the server open to unauthorized access and data interception. This vulnerability is particularly relevant in Go programming language where gRPC servers are often used for inter-service communication.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always use encryption and authentication when creating a gRPC server. This can be achieved by using Transport Layer Security (TLS) for encryption and token-based authentication for verifying the identity of clients.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to create a secure gRPC server with TLS and token-based authentication:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc\"\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\"\n)\n\n// Load the certificates from disk\ncert, err := tls.LoadX509KeyPair(\"server.crt\", \"server.key\")\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatalf(\"could not load server key pair: %s\", err)\n}\n\n// Create a TLS-based credential\ncreds := credentials.NewServerTLSFromCert(&cert)\n\n// Create a gRPC server object\ns.grpcServer = grpc.NewServer(grpc.Creds(creds))\n```\n\nIn this example, `server.crt` and `server.key` are the server's certificate and private key respectively. These files should be securely stored and accessible only by the server.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- google.golang.org/grpc\n- google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP gRPC Security](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/gRPC_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "653cf15d-6627-3f68-957c-5cceeab35314",
              "name": "Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rate; Recommendation for Storage in CDN or Cloud Buckets",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "This vulnerability pertains to the potential exposure of sensitive information due to the inclusion of unreadable files in scans, which can lead to a high false positive rate. In the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data such as API keys, tokens, or certificates are included in the code or configuration files that are being scanned. This can lead to the exposure of this sensitive information, which can be exploited by malicious actors.\n\nMitigation Advice:\n1. Avoid hardcoding sensitive information in the code or configuration files. Instead, use environment variables or secure vaults to store this information.\n2. Exclude unreadable files from scans to reduce the false positive rate. This can be achieved by configuring the scanning tool to ignore certain file types or directories.\n3. Store sensitive files in secure storage solutions such as Content Delivery Network (CDN) or Cloud Buckets. These solutions provide robust security features such as encryption and access control to protect the stored files.\n\nSource Code Fix Recommendation:\nThe provided code includes sensitive information such as server URLs and tokens in the `kubeConfig` string. This information should be removed from the code and stored securely. Here is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nkubeConfig := os.Getenv(\"KUBECONFIG\")\nnamespace := os.Getenv(\"NAMESPACE\")\nsecretName := os.Getenv(\"SECRET_NAME\")\n\nBody := []byte(`{\"kubeConfig\":\"` + kubeConfig + `\",\"namespace\":\"` + namespace + `\",\"secretName\":\"` + secretName + `\"}`),\n```\n\nIn this version, the sensitive information is retrieved from environment variables instead of being hardcoded in the code.\n\nLibrary Dependencies:\nThe provided code does not seem to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\nRelevant OWASP Resources:\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A3-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n\nMatching CWE:\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)\n- [CWE-532: Insertion of Sensitive Information into Log File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/532.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-532",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/532.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-200",
                  "CWE-532"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2ac643d8-699e-3dad-859f-913e32f30666",
              "name": "'printf' Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities. Use 'html/template' for User Data Rendering.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `fmt.Sprintf` function is used to format and return a string without printing it anywhere. When this function is used in conjunction with `http.ResponseWriter.Write()`, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because `fmt.Sprintf` does not escape HTML characters, which means that any user-supplied input can potentially include malicious scripts that will be executed in the browser of any user viewing the rendered HTML.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use the `html/template` package for user data rendering. This package automatically escapes any HTML characters, preventing the possibility of XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```go\nrw.Write([]byte(fmt.Sprintf(\"%s\\n\", level)))\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\ntmpl, err := template.New(\"test\").Parse(\"{.}\\n\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\nerr = tmpl.Execute(rw, level)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `fmt`\n- `net/http`\n- `html/template`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "56823dc4-171a-30f5-a7b3-d73f90c914ec",
              "name": "\"Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rates\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rates\" is not directly related to the Go programming language itself, but rather to the way how security scanning tools are configured. If a scanning tool is set to exclude unreadable files, it may lead to high false positive rates, as it might miss potential vulnerabilities in these files. This can lead to a false sense of security, as the scanning tool might report that the code is safe, while in reality, it contains vulnerabilities that were not detected due to the exclusion of unreadable files.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to configure the scanning tool to include all files, regardless of their readability. This will ensure that all potential vulnerabilities are detected and reported. Additionally, it is also recommended to regularly update the scanning tool to ensure that it is capable of detecting the latest vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code snippet does not directly relate to the vulnerability. However, if the code is part of a larger codebase that is being scanned, it is recommended to ensure that the scanning tool is configured to include all files, regardless of their readability.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE - 506: Embedded Malicious Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/506.html)\n\nPlease note that these links are subject to change and may not be accessible at all times. It is recommended to regularly check these links to ensure they are still active."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-506",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/506.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-506"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "345ea5ee-0e61-315d-967b-65247fc5d74f",
              "name": "Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rate; Recommendation for Storage in CDN or Cloud Buckets",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis vulnerability pertains to the exclusion of unreadable files from scans due to a high false positive rate. In the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the program is unable to read certain files during a scan, leading to a high rate of false positives. This can be a serious issue as it can lead to the overlooking of actual threats or vulnerabilities in the system. \n\nThe provided code example shows a JSON object being created with several fields, some of which contain URLs. If these URLs point to unreadable files, they could potentially trigger this vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to store files in a Content Delivery Network (CDN) or Cloud Buckets. These platforms often provide better file management and accessibility, reducing the chances of files being unreadable. \n\nAdditionally, it is important to ensure that the program has the necessary permissions to read all files it is expected to scan. This can be achieved by properly configuring the file system permissions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe source code fix would involve ensuring that all URLs in the JSON object point to readable files. This could be achieved by implementing a check before the JSON object is created to ensure all files are readable. \n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"net/http\"\n\t\"log\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\turls := []string{\n\t\t\"https://localhost:8443/v3/import/abcd.yaml\",\n\t\t// add more URLs here\n\t}\n\n\tfor _, url := range urls {\n\t\tresp, err := http.Get(url)\n\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n\t\t}\n\t\tdefer resp.Body.Close()\n\n\t\tif resp.StatusCode != http.StatusOK {\n\t\t\tlog.Fatalf(\"unable to read file: %s\", url)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\n\t// create JSON object here\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, a GET request is made to each URL before the JSON object is created. If any of the URLs point to an unreadable file, an error is logged and the program is terminated.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n- net/http\n- log\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)](https://cwe.mitre.org/index.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "33566730-28c5-3f08-8943-19c60ec89b8b",
              "name": "Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rate; Recommendation for Storage in CDN or Cloud Buckets",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "This vulnerability pertains to the potential risk of including unreadable files in scans, which can lead to a high false positive rate. In the context of Go programming language, this can occur when the program attempts to read or import data from a file or URL that is not readable or does not exist. This can lead to unexpected behavior or errors in the program.\n\nThe provided code example attempts to import data from a URL using the `curl` command. If the URL is not accessible or the data at the URL is not readable, this can lead to errors or unexpected behavior.\n\nMitigation Advice:\n1. Always validate and sanitize inputs: Ensure that the URL or file path is valid and accessible before attempting to read or import data from it.\n2. Handle errors properly: Implement proper error handling to catch and handle any errors that may occur during the reading or importing process.\n3. Use secure methods for data transfer: Instead of using insecure methods like `curl`, consider using secure methods for data transfer, such as HTTPS or SFTP.\n\nSource Code Fix Recommendation:\n```go\nbody := []byte(`{\"normalField\": \"some data\", \"manifestUrl\": \"https://localhost:8443/v3/import/abcd.yaml\"}`)\nurl := \"https://localhost:8443/v3/import/abcd.yaml\"\n\n// Validate the URL before using it\n_, err := url.ParseRequestURI(url)\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatal(err)\n}\n\n// Use secure methods for data transfer\nresp, err := http.Get(url)\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatal(err)\n}\ndefer resp.Body.Close()\n\n// Handle errors during the reading process\nbody, err := ioutil.ReadAll(resp.Body)\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatal(err)\n}\n```\nLibrary Dependencies:\n- Go standard library\n\nRelevant OWASP Resources:\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A3-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n\nMatching CWE:\n- [CWE-20: Improper Input Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html)\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-20",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-20",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "12d1adff-1d30-3859-80a6-98059d999477",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send data to the HTTP client. However, if user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, an error message is being written directly to the HTTP response. If the error message contains user-controlled data, this could potentially lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, user-controlled data should never be directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding. Instead, use context-specific output encoding libraries to ensure that the data is safe to display. For Go, the `html/template` package provides context-aware escaping functions that can be used to safely output user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"error\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(\"Failed to parse form: {{.}}\\n\")\nt.Execute(rw, err)\n```\n\nIn this version, the error message is safely outputted using the `html/template` package's context-aware escaping functions.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code snippet requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "24ef8e88-beec-35f7-8d28-a427e6146e8b",
              "name": "'printf' Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities: Use 'html/template' Package for User Data Rendering Instead.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `fmt.Sprintf` function is used to format and return a string without printing it anywhere. When this function is used in conjunction with `http.ResponseWriter.Write()`, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because `fmt.Sprintf` does not escape HTML characters, which means that if user-supplied data is included in the string being formatted, it could include malicious scripts that will be executed when the resulting string is rendered in a web browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use the `html/template` package for rendering user data. This package automatically escapes any HTML characters in the data, preventing the possibility of XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `fmt.Sprintf` and `http.ResponseWriter.Write()`, use `html/template` to render the data. Here is how you can modify the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"error\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(\"Failed to parse loglevel: {{.}}\\n\")\nt.Execute(rw, err)\n```\n\nIn this code, `t.Parse` is used to create a new template that includes the error message, and `t.Execute` is used to render this template directly to the `http.ResponseWriter`, with `err` as the data.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go, used for data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c242d0cf-551f-3c29-b4a6-ee020ecd8fd6",
              "name": "Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rate; Recommendation for Storage in CDN or Cloud Buckets",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis vulnerability pertains to the exclusion of unreadable files from scans due to a high false positive rate. In the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the program is unable to read certain files during a scan, leading to a high rate of false positives. This can be a serious issue as it can lead to the overlooking of actual threats or vulnerabilities in the system. \n\nThe provided code example shows a JSON object being created with several fields, some of which contain URLs. If these URLs point to unreadable files, they could potentially trigger this vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to store files in a Content Delivery Network (CDN) or Cloud Buckets. These platforms often provide better file management and accessibility, reducing the chances of files being unreadable. \n\nAdditionally, it is important to ensure that the program has the necessary permissions to read all files it is expected to scan. This can be achieved by properly configuring the file system permissions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe source code fix would involve ensuring that all URLs in the JSON object point to readable files. This could be achieved by implementing a check before the JSON object is created to ensure all files are readable. \n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"net/http\"\n\t\"log\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\turls := []string{\n\t\t\"https://localhost:8443/v3/import/abcd.yaml\",\n\t\t// add more URLs here\n\t}\n\n\tfor _, url := range urls {\n\t\tresp, err := http.Get(url)\n\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n\t\t}\n\t\tdefer resp.Body.Close()\n\n\t\tif resp.StatusCode != http.StatusOK {\n\t\t\tlog.Fatalf(\"unable to read file: %s\", url)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\n\t// create JSON object here\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, a GET request is made to each URL before the JSON object is created. If any of the URLs point to an unreadable file, an error is logged and the program is terminated.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n- net/http\n- log\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)](https://cwe.mitre.org/index.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
