            {
              "id": "cf7c22b9-81bb-3462-b8af-cbc98fe0666d",
              "name": "Potential Logic Bug Due to Variable 'err' Assigned from Two Different Sources",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Potential Logic Bug Due to Variable 'err' Assigned from Two Different Sources\" in Go programming language refers to a situation where a variable, in this case 'err', is assigned from two different sources. This can lead to confusion and potential bugs in the code. In the provided code snippet, 'err' is first assigned from the result of `io.ReadAll(req.Body)`, and then it is reassigned from the result of `json.Marshal(...)`. If the first operation fails and an error is assigned to 'err', the second operation might overwrite this error, making it difficult to understand what the original error was.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use separate error variables for different operations. This way, if an operation fails, its error will not be overwritten by subsequent operations.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nbody, err1 := io.ReadAll(req.Body)\nif err1 != nil {\n\tbody, err2 := json.Marshal(map[string]any{\n\t\t\"responseReadError\": err1.Error(),\n\t})\n\tif err2 != nil {\n\t\tbody = []byte(`{\"responseReadError\": \"failed to read response body\"}`)\n\t}\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, 'err1' is used for the error from `io.ReadAll(req.Body)` and 'err2' is used for the error from `json.Marshal(...)`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- `io`\n- `encoding/json`\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A6 - Security Misconfiguration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n- [CWE-691: Insufficient Control Flow Management](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/691.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-691",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/691.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-691"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c0fc2787-86a6-3410-a411-2e1d506d4ac0",
              "name": "\"Insecure TLS Configuration Object Creation Detection\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure TLS Configuration Object Creation Detection is a vulnerability that occurs when a TLS configuration object is created with insecure settings. In the provided Go code, the `MinVersion` field is set to `tls.VersionTLS10`, which means that the application will accept connections using TLS 1.0. This version of TLS is considered insecure and deprecated due to several known vulnerabilities, such as BEAST, CRIME and POODLE attacks.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should set the `MinVersion` field to a secure version of TLS. As of the time of writing, TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3 are considered secure. \n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nreturn &tls.Config{\n\tNextProtos:   []string{\"http/1.1\"},\n\tMinVersion:   tls.VersionTLS12,\n\tCertificates: []tls.Certificate{cert},\n\tRootCAs:      certPool,\n}, nil\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "67eea4ab-393f-3e06-a58b-c3a5668c3f41",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detection in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. This function does not perform any HTML escaping, which means that if untrusted user input is written directly to the HTTP response without proper sanitization, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize user input before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done by using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any HTML content when rendering templates. Additionally, you should also set the appropriate Content-Type header for your response to prevent the browser from interpreting the response as HTML if it's not intended to be.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```go\n_, _ = rw.Write(chunk[:writeSize])\n```\n\nYou should sanitize the user input using the `html/template` package:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(chunk[:writeSize]))\n_ = t.Execute(rw, nil)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package from the standard Go library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "de9c1a22-d11a-3c1f-83c6-89a249e84e5c",
              "name": "\"Potential Denial-of-Service Vulnerability through Zip Bomb Attack\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA potential Denial-of-Service (DoS) vulnerability through a Zip Bomb attack can occur in Go programming language when an application does not properly handle the decompression of zip files. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it. It is often employed to disable antivirus software, in order to create an opening for more traditional viruses.\n\nIn the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when using the `io.Copy` function to read from a `tarReader` into a `buf`. If the `tarReader` is reading from a Zip Bomb, it could potentially consume all available memory and crash the system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should limit the amount of data that can be read from a `tarReader` into a `buf`. This can be done by wrapping the `tarReader` in an `io.LimitReader`, which will stop reading from the `tarReader` after a certain amount of data has been read.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to use `io.LimitReader` to limit the amount of data read from a `tarReader`:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"archive/tar\"\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    // Open the tar file\n    f, _ := os.Open(\"file.tar\")\n    defer f.Close()\n\n    // Create a new tar reader\n    tarReader := tar.NewReader(f)\n\n    // Create a buffer to hold the data\n    buf := make([]byte, 1024)\n\n    // Wrap the tarReader in an io.LimitReader\n    limitReader := io.LimitReader(tarReader, 1024*1024) // Limit to 1MB\n\n    // Copy from the limitReader (instead of the tarReader) to the buf\n    _, err := io.Copy(buf, limitReader)\n    if err != nil {\n        // Handle error\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `archive/tar`\n- `io`\n- `os`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2a3f8487-01f3-348f-b0b0-990cbf7bd892",
              "name": "\"Potential Denial-of-Service Vulnerability through Zip Bomb Attack\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA potential Denial-of-Service (DoS) vulnerability through a Zip Bomb attack can occur in Go programming language when an application does not properly handle the decompression of zip files. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it. It is often employed to disable antivirus software, in order to create an opening for more traditional viruses.\n\nIn the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when using the `io.Copy` function to read from a `tarReader` into a `buf`. If the `tarReader` is reading from a Zip Bomb, it could potentially consume all available memory and crash the system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should limit the amount of data that can be read from a `tarReader` into a `buf`. This can be done by wrapping the `tarReader` in an `io.LimitReader`, which will stop reading from the `tarReader` after a certain amount of data has been read.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to use `io.LimitReader` to limit the amount of data read from a `tarReader`:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"archive/tar\"\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    // Open the tar file\n    f, _ := os.Open(\"file.tar\")\n    defer f.Close()\n\n    // Create a new tar reader\n    tarReader := tar.NewReader(f)\n\n    // Create a buffer to hold the data\n    buf := make([]byte, 1024)\n\n    // Wrap the tarReader in an io.LimitReader\n    limitReader := io.LimitReader(tarReader, 1024*1024) // Limit to 1MB\n\n    // Copy from the limitReader (instead of the tarReader) to the buf\n    _, err := io.Copy(buf, limitReader)\n    if err != nil {\n        // Handle error\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `archive/tar`\n- `io`\n- `os`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
