            {
              "id": "47d31b31-48cc-30ce-bbf2-24ed4d1aeb90",
              "name": "\"Possible Denial-of-Service Vulnerability Detected through Zip Bomb Attack\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA Denial-of-Service (DoS) vulnerability can occur in Go programming language when a Zip Bomb attack is executed. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it, by consuming large amounts of system resources. This is typically done by creating an archive file that decompresses to a much larger size, effectively causing resource exhaustion.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises when the `io.Copy` function is used to copy data from a `tarReader` to a `file`. If the `tarReader` is reading from a Zip Bomb, this could lead to excessive consumption of system resources, potentially causing a Denial-of-Service.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should implement a mechanism to limit the amount of data that can be read from an archive file. This could be done by wrapping the `tarReader` in a `io.LimitedReader`, which imposes a limit on the number of bytes read.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nconst maxBytes = 1 << 20 // Limit to 1MB\n\nfile, _ := os.Create(\"file.txt\")\ntarReader, _ := os.Open(\"archive.tar\")\n\nlimitedReader := &io.LimitedReader{R: tarReader, N: maxBytes}\n_, err = io.Copy(file, limitedReader)\n\nif err != nil {\n    // Handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `io.LimitedReader` is used to limit the number of bytes read from `tarReader` to `maxBytes` (1MB in this case). This prevents excessive consumption of system resources even if a Zip Bomb is read.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `io`\n- `os`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption ('Resource Exhaustion')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6b9ac3fb-768e-3baa-9320-0baf35299671",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure and deprecated due to its vulnerability to collision attacks. In a collision attack, an attacker can generate a different input that hashes to the same MD5 hash as a legitimate input, thereby bypassing security controls. This vulnerability is particularly critical in cryptographic protections, password storage, and data integrity checks.\n\nIn Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package provides the MD5 hash algorithm, which is insecure. It is recommended to use more secure hash algorithms such as SHA-256 or SHA-3 provided by the `crypto/sha256` and `crypto/sha3` packages respectively.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, replace the use of MD5 with a more secure hash algorithm. SHA-256 or SHA-3 are recommended as they are currently considered secure and resistant to known types of cryptographic attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `crypto/md5` with `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3`. Here is an example of how to use SHA-256:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/sha256\"\n\nhasher := sha256.New()\n```\n\nOr, if you prefer to use SHA-3:\n\n```go\nimport \"golang.org/x/crypto/sha3\"\n\nhasher := sha3.New256()\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- For MD5: `\"crypto/md5\"`\n- For SHA-256: `\"crypto/sha256\"`\n- For SHA-3: `\"golang.org/x/crypto/sha3\"`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f9dedab6-4cee-368b-b34d-b624c70bd700",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Export in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Export in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake where a pointer to a loop variable is incorrectly used within a goroutine or a closure. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all iterations of the loop might end up using the same variable, which is the one that the pointer points to in the last iteration of the loop.\n\nIn the provided code, the issue might occur if the `tt` variable is used inside the `t.Run` function, which is a closure. If `tt` is a pointer, all tests might end up using the same `tt` value, which is the one from the last iteration of the loop.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this issue, you should avoid using pointers to loop variables inside goroutines or closures. Instead, you should pass the loop variable as an argument to the goroutine or closure, or you should create a new variable inside the loop and use that instead.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n    tt := tt // Create a new variable to use inside the closure\n    t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        // The rest of the code remains the same\n    })\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a new `tt` variable is created in each iteration of the loop, and this new variable is used inside the closure. This ensures that each test uses the correct `tt` value.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to depend on the following libraries:\n\n- `testing`: a standard Go library for testing Go code.\n- `net/http`: a standard Go library for building HTTP clients and servers.\n- `net/http/httptest`: a standard Go library for testing HTTP clients and servers.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-118: Incorrect Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n\nPlease note that the links are valid and active at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-118",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-118"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c6c38fe9-65e3-3e89-abeb-71f9c0cf29a5",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability due to Modification of `secret` Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability due to the modification of the `secret` variable. This vulnerability occurs when the program attempts to access or modify a memory location through a pointer that points to a `nil` or `null` value. In this case, the `secret` variable is being accessed after a potential error condition, which could lead to a nil dereference if the `secret` is `nil`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always check if a pointer is `nil` before accessing or modifying its value. This can be done by adding an additional condition to check if the `secret` variable is `nil` before accessing its `Name` property.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\nsecret, err := secretClient.Get(ctx, secretRef.Name, metav1.GetOptions{})\nif err != nil {\n\t// During the encryption key update this can fail for deleted secrets.\n\t// This manifests as an Internal Error from K8s.\n\t// In this case, we can ignore it and let a secret be created.\n\tif !apierrors.IsInternalError(err) {\n\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"could not get secret for service account: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\tif secret != nil {\n\t\tlogrus.Infof(\"internal error when getting a secret %s - not using the secret\", secret.Name)\n\t}\n\treturn nil, nil\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- `context`\n- `fmt`\n- `github.com/sirupsen/logrus`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/api/errors`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A2:2017 Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "5cb0a6e9-d974-3f9b-a5a4-80c4ac64b4ed",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic uses because it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, which can lead to security vulnerabilities. In the context of Go programming language, if you're using `md5.Sum([]byte(input))` to generate a hash of some input, an attacker could potentially find another input that produces the same hash, leading to a collision attack.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe general advice to mitigate this vulnerability is to use a more secure hash algorithm, such as SHA256 or SHA3. These algorithms are currently considered secure against collision attacks and are recommended for most cryptographic uses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can modify your code to use SHA256 instead of MD5:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/sha256\"\n\nhash := sha256.Sum256([]byte(machine.RequestedHostname))\n```\n\nOr, if you prefer to use SHA3:\n\n```go\nimport \"golang.org/x/crypto/sha3\"\n\nhash := sha3.Sum256([]byte(machine.RequestedHostname))\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- For SHA256: `crypto/sha256`\n- For SHA3: `golang.org/x/crypto/sha3`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "29cbc18f-2fdc-31bf-9524-f27ad3ca5781",
              "name": "\"Insecure MinVersion of TLS Configuration Objects Detection\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Insecure MinVersion of TLS Configuration Objects Detection\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure configuration of the minimum version of the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol. In the provided code snippet, the minimum version of TLS is set to `tls.VersionTLS10`, which is considered insecure. This is because older versions of TLS, such as TLS 1.0 and 1.1, have known vulnerabilities and are not recommended for secure communications.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a secure version of TLS, such as TLS 1.2 or 1.3. This can be done by setting the `MinVersion` field of the `tls.Config` struct to `tls.VersionTLS12` or `tls.VersionTLS13`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\ncfg: &tls.Config{\n    MinVersion:   tls.VersionTLS12,\n    CipherSuites: []uint16{tls.TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384, tls.TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256},\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "278b6842-7bae-3767-b527-9673eaee1fa9",
              "name": "\"Insecure MinVersion of TLS Configuration Objects Detection\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Insecure MinVersion of TLS Configuration Objects Detection\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure configuration of the minimum version of the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol. In the provided code snippet, the minimum version of TLS is set to `tls.VersionTLS11`, which is considered insecure. This is because TLS 1.1 and earlier versions have known vulnerabilities and are deprecated. Using these versions can expose the application to various security risks, including man-in-the-middle attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should use a secure version of TLS. As of now, the recommended minimum version is TLS 1.2. However, it is always a good practice to use the latest stable version of TLS, which is currently TLS 1.3.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\ncfg: &tls.Config{\n    MinVersion:   tls.VersionTLS13,\n    CipherSuites: []uint16{tls.TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384, tls.TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256},\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "817df0ab-be4b-392b-bd42-ebd87e91218a",
              "name": "\"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "The \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior. This vulnerability occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is shared across multiple goroutines. The problem arises because the loop variable is reused across iterations, and when the loop variable changes, all goroutines see this change. This can lead to race conditions where some goroutines might not process the correct data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing loop variables across goroutines. Instead, you should create a new variable within the scope of the loop and use that variable instead. This ensures that each goroutine has its own copy of the variable, preventing race conditions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, v := range v {\n    v := v // create a new 'v' variable\n    if pairMatches(v, f) {\n        return true\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a new 'v' variable is created within the scope of the loop. This new variable is used instead of the loop variable, ensuring that each goroutine has its own copy of the variable.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies. However, the `pairMatches` function is not defined, so it's possible that it could require additional libraries.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)\n\nPlease note that these links are subject to change and may not always be accessible."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-362",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-362"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "76228fc2-5e44-3175-878a-831f8ed792ca",
              "name": "User-Input Crafted HTTP Redirect Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"User-Input Crafted HTTP Redirect Vulnerability Detected\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when an application accepts user-controlled input and uses this input in a server-side redirect. This can allow an attacker to craft a URL that, if clicked, may redirect users to an arbitrary website where they could be subject to phishing attacks, or the downloading and execution of malicious code.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Redirect` function is used with unvalidated user input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to validate all user inputs before using them in server-side functions. Specifically, for URLs, it is advisable to check if the URL is in a list of trusted URLs before redirecting. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix for the specific vulnerability sink:\n\n```go\ntrustedUrls := map[string]bool{\n    \"http://trusted1.com\": true,\n    \"http://trusted2.com\": true,\n    // add more trusted URLs here\n}\n\nu, err := url.ParseRequestURI(userInput)\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatal(err)\n}\n\n_, exists := trustedUrls[u.String()]\nif !exists {\n    log.Fatal(\"URL is not trusted\")\n}\n\nhttp.Redirect(rw, req, u.String(), http.StatusFound)\n```\n\nIn this code, we first parse the user input to a URL. Then we check if the URL exists in our map of trusted URLs. If it does not exist, we log an error and stop the execution. If it does exist, we proceed with the redirection.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: for the `http.Redirect` function and `http.StatusFound` constant.\n- `net/url`: for the `url.ParseRequestURI` function.\n- `log`: for the `log.Fatal` function.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-601"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1bcf1b6f-0815-3d61-a206-8763e8462f35",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes user-controlled data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user-controlled data to the HTTP response, use the `html/template` package to render HTML templates. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    t, _ := template.ParseFiles(\"template.html\")\n    data := map[string]string{\n        \"UserControlledData\": r.URL.Query().Get(\"data\"),\n    }\n    t.Execute(w, data)\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.html` file should contain `{{.UserControlledData}}` where the user-controlled data should be inserted. The `html/template` package will automatically HTML escape the data.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `net/http` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n- The `html/template` package, which is also part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "04f0dd42-f63d-3836-87c4-418cba482468",
              "name": "\"Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic uses because it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, making it possible for an attacker to substitute a malicious input for a legitimate one without detection. In the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 checksum (a type of hash function) of data.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `md5.Sum` function is used to generate a unique identifier based on the current time. This could potentially be exploited if an attacker is able to predict or control the time value used as input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a more secure hash algorithm such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure against collision attacks and are suitable for most cryptographic uses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `md5.Sum` with `sha256.Sum256` or `sha3.Sum256` from the `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3` packages respectively. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    h := sha256.New()\n    h.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following Go standard library packages:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "cecd7098-b8bc-3ff0-8567-7842ac727752",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Cookie` struct is used to create a cookie without the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields set to `true`. The `Secure` field ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted in transit. The `HttpOnly` field prevents the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, mitigating the risk of cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields to `true` when creating a cookie. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over secure connections and cannot be accessed through client-side scripts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nr.AddCookie(&http.Cookie{\n\tName:     tokens.CookieName,\n\tValue:    bearerToken,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Secure Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "dc911434-53a5-3c64-bf1f-1f66bb254373",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Export Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Export Vulnerability\" is a common vulnerability in Go programming language where the developer unintentionally shares a pointer to a variable in a loop. This can lead to unexpected behavior and potential security issues as the same memory location is being accessed and modified concurrently.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, there is no direct pointer sharing vulnerability. However, the code is vulnerable to LDAP Injection attacks. The `ldap.SanitizeAttr(attr)` and `ldapv3.EscapeFilter(name)` functions are used to sanitize the `attr` and `name` variables respectively, but if these functions are not implemented correctly, an attacker could inject malicious LDAP queries.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, ensure that all user-supplied input is properly sanitized and validated. Avoid constructing LDAP queries using string concatenation with user-supplied input. Instead, use parameterized queries or other safe APIs.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe code fix would depend on the implementation of the `ldap.SanitizeAttr` and `ldapv3.EscapeFilter` functions. Assuming these functions are not properly sanitizing the input, a possible fix could be:\n\n```go\nfor _, attr := range srchAttributes {\n    sanitizedAttr := ldap.SanitizeAttr(attr)\n    escapedName := ldapv3.EscapeFilter(name)\n    if sanitizedAttr != \"\" && escapedName != \"\" {\n        srchAttrs += fmt.Sprintf(\"(%s=%s*)\", sanitizedAttr, escapedName)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we only add the attribute to `srchAttrs` if both `sanitizedAttr` and `escapedName` are not empty. This ensures that only valid attributes and names are added to the LDAP query.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `fmt`\n- `ldap`\n- `ldapv3`\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-20: Improper Input Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-20",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-20"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "086759cd-6cc5-316e-b121-ac4e1f0fe4a4",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior and potential security issues. This vulnerability occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is used within a goroutine or deferred function. Since the loop variable is reused across iterations, the pointer will always point to the last value of the loop variable, which may not be what the programmer intended.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using pointers to loop variables within goroutines or deferred functions. Instead, you should create a new variable within the loop scope and use a pointer to that variable.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, principal := range principals {\n    p := principal\n    p.Me = common.SamePrincipal(token.GetUserPrincipal(), &p)\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a new variable `p` is created for each iteration of the loop. This ensures that each goroutine or deferred function gets its own unique copy of the loop variable, preventing the unintentional pointer sharing.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it seems to be using a custom `common` package for the `SamePrincipal` function and a custom `token` package for the `GetUserPrincipal` function. The `principals` slice seems to contain custom `Principal` objects.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [CWE-567: Unsynchronized Access to Shared Data in a Multithreaded Context](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/567.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-567",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/567.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-567"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e7ce9c0a-2789-3d2e-8401-2e4f68c30d4b",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration defaults to insecure TLS1.0, set it to a secure version like `VersionTLS13`.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `tls.Config` struct is used to configure TLS (Transport Layer Security) clients and servers. If the `MinVersion` field in `tls.Config` is not set, it defaults to TLS 1.0, which is considered insecure due to several known vulnerabilities. This could potentially expose the application to various attacks such as BEAST, CRIME and POODLE.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should explicitly set the `MinVersion` field to a secure version of TLS, such as `tls.VersionTLS13`.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is how you can fix the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\ntlsConfig = &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs:            caPool,\n    InsecureSkipVerify: false,\n    ServerName:         server,\n    MinVersion:         tls.VersionTLS13,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This is a built-in Go library for TLS support.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1ae15cde-e973-367d-a21e-6706c6847eaa",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" is a common vulnerability in Go programming language where the developer unintentionally shares a pointer to a loop variable in goroutines or closures. This can lead to unexpected behavior as all goroutines or closures might end up referring to the last value of the loop variable.\n\nIn the provided code, the vulnerability does not seem to be present as the loop variable `tt` is not being shared across multiple goroutines. However, if `tt` was used inside a goroutine or closure that is invoked asynchronously, it could lead to this vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing loop variables in goroutines or closures. If you need to use the loop variable inside a goroutine or closure, you should pass it as an argument or create a new variable inside the goroutine or closure that holds the value of the loop variable.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code does not seem to have the \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\". However, if `tt` was used inside a goroutine, the code should be fixed as follows:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n\ttt := tt // create a new variable that holds the value of tt\n\tgo func() {\n\t\t// use tt inside the goroutine\n\t}()\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to require the following libraries:\n\n- `testing`: standard library for testing in Go.\n- `common`: a custom library, not specified in the provided code.\n- `apimgmtv3`: a custom library, not specified in the provided code.\n- `assert`: a library for assertions, possibly `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`.\n- `require`: a library for assertions, possibly `github.com/stretchr/testify/require`.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-118: Improper Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-118",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-118"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "911bc31f-ded4-3908-9f59-efffa59c5cf2",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior and potential security vulnerabilities. This vulnerability occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is shared across multiple goroutines. Since the loop variable is reused across iterations, all goroutines might end up referring to the last value of the loop variable, leading to race conditions and data inconsistencies.\n\nIn the provided code, the `test` variable from the loop is being used inside a goroutine which is potentially problematic. The `test` variable is a single instance that is reused in each iteration of the loop, and when the loop finishes, `test` will always be the last item in `testCases`. This means that all functions passed to `t.Run` will share the same `test` instance, which is not what we want.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables across goroutines. Instead, you should pass the loop variable as an argument to the goroutine or create a new variable within the scope of the goroutine.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nfor _, test := range testCases {\n    test := test // create a new 'test' variable\n    t.Run(test.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        t.Parallel()\n        // ... rest of the code ...\n    })\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a new `test` variable is created in each iteration of the loop, ensuring that each goroutine has its own `test` instance.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `github.com/golang/mock/gomock`\n- `k8s.io/client-go/tools/cache`\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1`\n- `github.com/rancher/types/apis/management.cattle.io/v3`\n\n## References\n\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE-362): Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)\n\nPlease note that the links were active and accessible at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-362",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-362"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1c8a01f4-f681-35d2-94c1-baf5a786fe03",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" is a common vulnerability in Go programming language where the developer unintentionally shares a pointer to a loop variable in goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines share the same instance of the loop variable, which can be updated by any goroutine. In the provided code, the `test` variable is shared across multiple goroutines, which can lead to race conditions.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing loop variables in goroutines. Instead, you should pass the loop variable as an argument to the goroutine function or create a new variable within the scope of the goroutine.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nfor _, test := range tests {\n    test := test // create a new 'test' variable\n    t.Run(test.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        t.Parallel()\n        result, err := provider.TransformToAuthProvider(test.authConfig)\n        assert.NoError(t, err)\n        assert.Equal(t, test.expected, result)\n    })\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a new `test` variable is created within the scope of the loop. This ensures that each goroutine has its own `test` variable, preventing race conditions.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `testing`: a standard Go library for testing Go code.\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`: a Go library providing a set of assertions for writing tests in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-362",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-362"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3cad5a5a-3ebf-34eb-a895-741cbf9df8dc",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping: Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping: Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerability\" in Go programming language refers to a situation where untrusted user input is directly written to an HTTP response without proper sanitization or escaping. This can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks, where an attacker can inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape untrusted user input before writing it to an HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package, which automatically escapes user input when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user input to the HTTP response, use the `html/template` package to safely render user input in HTML templates. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"userOrgs\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, userOrgs)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `{{.}}` is a placeholder for the user input, which is automatically escaped by the `html/template` package.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The Go standard library (no additional dependencies are needed)\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
