            {
              "id": "69beecc4-ed50-35bf-b535-a76a8d7b226b",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform any HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the user input will be executed by the browser.\n\nThis vulnerability is particularly dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser or system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data inserted into a template.\n\nIn addition, you should also implement a Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict the execution of scripts in your web pages. This can help to mitigate the impact of any XSS vulnerabilities that may still exist in your application.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the user-controlled input to the HTTP response, you should use a template to insert the data. Here is an example of how you can do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"teams\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, org2Teams)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.New(\"teams\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")` line creates a new template that includes the user-controlled input. The `t.Execute(w, org2Teams)` line then inserts the data into the template and writes the result to the HTTP response. The `html/template` package automatically escapes the data, so any HTML or JavaScript code in the input will not be executed by the browser.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
