            {
              "id": "830af436-2563-3775-b354-a84dfc829f54",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform any HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the input will be executed by the browser.\n\nThis vulnerability is particularly dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data inserted into a template.\n\nIn addition, you should follow the principle of least privilege by only allowing necessary permissions to your application. Regularly update and patch all systems to minimize the risk of security vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user-controlled input to the HTTP response, you should use a template and insert the input into the template. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"teams\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, orgTeams)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `t.Execute(w, orgTeams)` writes the `orgTeams` data to the HTTP response, but any HTML or JavaScript code in `orgTeams` is automatically escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
