                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, this function does not automatically escape HTML characters. If the data written to the response contains user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because an attacker can inject malicious scripts into the data, which will then be executed in the browser of any user who views the response.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input that is included in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes HTML characters when rendering templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user-controlled input to the response, you should use a template to render the data. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"userGroup\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, searchUsersGroup)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `{{.}}` is a placeholder for the data that will be rendered in the template. The `template.Execute()` function automatically escapes any HTML characters in the data.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
