            {
              "id": "d00a0fc3-f104-3053-a0d3-ee6cceb29e0d",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Export in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unintentional Pointer Export in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common programming mistake where a developer unintentionally shares a pointer to a variable in multiple iterations of a loop. This can lead to unexpected behavior and potential security vulnerabilities, as changes to the variable in one iteration can affect its value in subsequent iterations.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `acc` variable is a pointer that is being passed to the `g.toPrincipal` function in each iteration of the loop. If `g.toPrincipal` stores this pointer for later use, it will always point to the last `account` in the `accounts` slice, not the `account` that was current during the call.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop iteration variables. Instead, you should create a new variable in each iteration and share a pointer to that variable.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nfor _, acc := range accounts {\n    accCopy := acc\n    principals = append(principals, g.toPrincipal(accCopy.Type, &accCopy, token))\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, we create a new variable `accCopy` in each iteration and pass a pointer to `accCopy` to `g.toPrincipal`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not include enough context to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it appears to use a custom type or package `g` and a custom type `account`, which would need to be defined elsewhere in the code or imported from a library.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-567: Unsynchronized Access to Shared Data in a Multithreaded Context](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/567.html)\n\nPlease note that the CWE link is a best match based on the provided code snippet and may not perfectly match the exact vulnerability."
              },
              "properties": {
