            {
              "id": "dac6ac07-8945-38df-84c5-ad8d2acda66c",
              "name": "Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "The \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior. This vulnerability occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is shared across multiple goroutines. The Go runtime schedules goroutines on available logical processors, which means that the order of execution for goroutines is not guaranteed. If a loop variable is shared across goroutines, it's possible that the variable will be updated by one goroutine while another is still using it, leading to unpredictable results.\n\nMitigation Advice:\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables across goroutines. Instead, you should pass the actual value to the goroutine or create a new variable within the scope of the loop and pass a pointer to that variable.\n\nSource Code Fix Recommendation:\n\nIn the provided code, there is no shared loop pointer vulnerability. The loop variable `tt` is not shared across multiple goroutines. Each iteration of the loop runs a test in its own goroutine, but the test does not spawn any additional goroutines that could access `tt`. Therefore, no fix is needed for this code.\n\nLibrary Dependencies:\n\nThe code example appears to require the following libraries:\n\n- `testing`: standard library for testing Go code.\n- `reflect`: standard library for accessing type metadata.\n- A library that provides the `ldapProvider` and `mockGenericClient` types. The exact library is not specified in the code.\n\nOWASP Resources:\n\n\nCWE:\n\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)"
              },
