            {
              "id": "801ce44e-873f-330a-aa1a-591475e972e9",
              "name": "\"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "The \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake where the developer uses a pointer to a loop variable from a goroutine or a defer statement. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines and defer statements will share the same instance of the loop variable, which can be updated by subsequent iterations. This can lead to race conditions and data inconsistencies, especially in concurrent scenarios.\n\nMitigation Advice:\n\n1. Avoid using pointers to loop variables in goroutines or defer statements.\n2. If you need to use the loop variable inside a goroutine or a defer statement, create a local copy of the variable inside the loop.\n\nSource Code Fix Recommendation:\n\n```go\nfor _, tc := range testCases {\n    tc := tc // create a local copy of tc\n    t.Run(tc.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        ctx, err := AddCertKeyToContext(context.Background(), tc.cert, tc.key)\n        assert.Equal(t, err != nil, tc.shouldFail)\n        if tc.shouldFail && err != nil {\n            return\n        }\n\n        got, ok := ctx.Value(oauth2.HTTPClient).(*http.Client)\n        require.True(t, ok, \"expected to find an http client accessible in the context but didn't\")\n\n        gotTransport := got.Transport.(*http.Transport)\n        if !gotTransport.TLSClientConfig.RootCAs.Equal(tc.wantPool) {\n            t.Fatalf(\"system cert pool did not match desired\")\n        }\n\n        assert.Equal(t, tc.wantCerts, gotTransport.TLSClientConfig.Certificates, \"cert did not match desired\")\n    })\n}\n```\n\nLibrary Dependencies:\n\n1. context\n2. testing\n3. oauth2\n4. http\n5. assert\n6. require\n\nOWASP Resources:\n\n\nCommon Weakness Enumeration (CWE):\n\n- [CWE-552: Files or Directories Accessible to External Parties](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/552.html)\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-552",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/552.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-362",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-552",
                  "CWE-362"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b4e88f6e-5f7a-3e54-8ee6-6d94c09f3848",
              "name": "\"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when the address of a loop variable is shared across multiple goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines will reference the same variable, which will hold the value of the last iteration.\n\nIn the provided code, the `tc` variable is a loop variable that is captured by the function literal inside the `t.Run` function. This function literal is potentially executed in a separate goroutine, which can lead to data races if multiple test cases are run concurrently.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing the address of a loop variable across multiple goroutines. Instead, you should create a new variable within the scope of the loop and use that variable instead.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nfor _, tc := range testCases {\n    tc := tc // Fix: create a new variable within the scope of the loop\n    t.Run(tc.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        server := httptest.NewServer(http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n            w.WriteHeader(tc.mockStatus)\n            w.Write([]byte(tc.mockResponse))\n        }))\n        defer server.Close()\n\n        // Adjust the config to use the mock server URL\n        if _, ok := tc.config[\"issuer\"].(string); ok {\n            mockURL, _ := url.Parse(server.URL)\n            tc.config[\"issuer\"] = mockURL.Scheme + \"://\" + mockURL.Host\n        }\n\n        authURL, err := FetchAuthURL(tc.config)\n        if (err != nil) != tc.expectError {\n            t.Fatalf(\"expected error: %v, got: %v\", tc.expectError, err)\n        }\n        if authURL != tc.expectedURL {\n            t.Fatalf(\"expected URL: %s, got: %s\", tc.expectedURL, authURL)\n        }\n    })\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`\n- `net/http/httptest`\n- `net/url`\n- `testing`\n\n## References\n\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE-118)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-118",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-118"
