            {
              "id": "a33c9f42-3127-3b4d-aaea-a46fabf163ff",
              "name": "Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior and potential security issues. This vulnerability occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is shared across multiple goroutines. The problem arises because all goroutines share the same instance of the loop variable, which can be updated by any goroutine. This can lead to race conditions where the value of the variable is not what is expected when it is accessed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables across goroutines. Instead, you should pass the actual value of the variable to the goroutine. This ensures that each goroutine has its own copy of the variable, preventing race conditions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, v := range data {\n    val := v // create a new variable to hold the value of v\n    storedOidcConfig.ClientSecret = string(val)\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, we create a new variable `val` to hold the value of `v` for each iteration of the loop. This ensures that the value used to set `storedOidcConfig.ClientSecret` is not shared across multiple goroutines.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
