            {
              "id": "5144cdc0-992c-3340-9ff0-d8f8634467e2",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a raw HTTP response to a client. If user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper HTML escaping, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS attacks occur when an attacker can inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always escape user-controlled data before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes all data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the user-controlled data to the HTTP response, you should use an HTML template to render the response. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"response\").Parse(tc.mockResponse)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, data)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `tc.mockResponse` is a string that defines an HTML template, and `data` is a struct that contains the data to be included in the response. The `template.Execute()` function automatically escapes all data before including it in the response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8e56bc40-d3b9-3bde-9655-7d4392762335",
              "name": "\"Session cookie lacks 'HttpOnly' flag setting, posing XSS attack vulnerability.\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Session cookie lacks 'HttpOnly' flag setting, posing XSS attack vulnerability\" refers to a situation where a session cookie is not marked with the 'HttpOnly' flag. This can potentially expose the application to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. In such attacks, malicious scripts are injected into trusted websites, which can lead to unauthorized access, data theft, and other security breaches.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if the 'HttpOnly' flag is not set to true when creating a new cookie. In the provided code snippet, the 'HttpOnly' flag is not set for the `pkceCookie`, which means that the cookie can be accessed through client-side scripts, making it vulnerable to XSS attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to set the 'HttpOnly' flag to true when creating a new cookie. This will prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, effectively protecting it from XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\npkceCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     pkceVerifierCookieName,\n\tValue:    \"\",\n\tSecure:   isSecure,\n\tHttpOnly: true, // Set HttpOnly flag to true\n\tExpires:  time.Now().Add(time.Second * -10),\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: for creating and managing HTTP requests and responses, including cookies.\n- `time`: for manipulating time values, such as setting the cookie expiration time.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://owasp.org/www-community/HttpOnly)\n- [OWASP - Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "38540a8e-751a-37a0-8c86-9cbb0785db3d",
              "name": "Unintended Public Server Exposure due to Binding to All Interfaces",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the vulnerability \"Unintended Public Server Exposure due to Binding to All Interfaces\" occurs when a network service is unintentionally exposed to the public internet. This happens when the service binds to all network interfaces (0.0.0.0 or ::), instead of binding to localhost (127.0.0.1 or ::1). This can lead to unauthorized access to the service, data leakage, or even remote code execution.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `net.Listen(\"tcp\", \":0\")` function call binds the listener to all network interfaces, which can expose the server to the public internet.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should bind your service to localhost (127.0.0.1 or ::1) unless it is necessary for the service to be accessible from the public internet. This will ensure that the service is only accessible from the local machine.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nlistener, err := net.Listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:0\") // bind to localhost and choose any available port\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet only requires the `net` package from the standard library of Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-284: Improper Access Control](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/284.html)"
              },
