            {
              "id": "d37c618b-9034-34a4-a869-df22e52c09a6",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal a user's session cookie and impersonate them. In the provided Go code, the vulnerability arises from the `Secure` field of the `http.Cookie` struct being set to `isSecure`, which may not always be `true`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` field of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted by an attacker. Additionally, consider setting the `SameSite` field to `http.SameSiteStrictMode` or `http.SameSiteLaxMode` to prevent the cookie from being sent with cross-site requests.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nimport \"net/http\"\n\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     \"R_SESS\",\n\tValue:    rToken.ObjectMeta.Name + \":\" + unhashedTokenKey,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tSameSite: http.SameSiteStrictMode,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the `net/http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
