            {
              "id": "327910ab-2b38-3992-ba31-88ec1433b93f",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal a user's session cookie and impersonate them.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` attribute of the cookie is set to `true` only if the `Secure` field of the `c` object is `true` or if the scheme of the request URL is \"https\". This means that if neither of these conditions is met, the cookie will be sent over an unsecured connection, making it vulnerable to interception.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of cookies to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which encrypts the data and prevents it from being intercepted.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nhttp.SetCookie(w, &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     stateCookiePrefix + id,\n\tValue:    value,\n\tMaxAge:   int(saml.MaxIssueDelay.Seconds()),\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     path,\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following libraries:\n\n- `net/http`: Provides HTTP client and server implementations.\n- `github.com/crewjam/saml`: Provides SAML support.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Secure Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
