            {
              "id": "f4f7b570-2948-3705-836c-b4a6effbda60",
              "name": "Potential Logic Bug Due to Variable 'err' Assigned from Two Different Sources",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Potential Logic Bug Due to Variable 'err' Assigned from Two Different Sources\" refers to a situation where a variable, in this case 'err', is assigned from two different sources. This can lead to confusion and potential bugs as the value of 'err' can be overwritten by the second assignment, potentially masking an error from the first assignment.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the variable 'err' is assigned multiple times from different sources. This can lead to a situation where an error from one function call is overwritten by the next function call, potentially masking important error information.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this issue, it is recommended to handle each error immediately after it occurs. This can be done by checking if 'err' is not nil right after the function call and then handling the error appropriately. This ensures that each error is handled at the source and not overwritten by subsequent function calls.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```go\nerr = s.setRancherToken(w, s.tokenMGR, user.Name, userPrincipal, groupPrincipals, true)\nif err != nil {\n\tlog.Errorf(\"SAML: Failed creating token with error: %v\", err)\n\thttp.Redirect(w, r, redirectURL+\"errorCode=500\", http.StatusFound)\n\treturn\n}\n\n// Rest of the code...\n```\n\nIn the above code, we return immediately after redirecting in case of an error. This ensures that the error is handled immediately and not overwritten by subsequent function calls.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to depend on the following libraries:\n\n- net/http\n- log\n- encoding/base64\n- encoding/json\n- crypto/rand\n- crypto/rsa\n- crypto/sha256\n- fmt\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-691: Insufficient Control Flow Management](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/691.html)"
