            {
              "id": "1fbfbf53-3358-3c80-947c-5181a63bafbc",
              "name": "Potential Logic Bug Due to Reading 'FinalRedirectURL' from Two Different Sources",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis vulnerability arises when the 'FinalRedirectURL' is read from two different sources. This can lead to a potential logic bug in the Go programming language. The bug can cause unexpected behavior in the application, potentially leading to security vulnerabilities such as unauthorized access or data leakage.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to ensure that 'FinalRedirectURL' is read from a single, trusted source. This can prevent potential inconsistencies and logic bugs. Additionally, it is important to validate and sanitize all inputs and outputs to prevent other potential security vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe source code fix would involve ensuring that 'FinalRedirectURL' is read from a single source. Here is a possible fix:\n\n```go\nusernames := userAttributes.ExtraByProvider[providerName][\"username\"]\nif len(usernames) == 0 {\n\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"SAML [logout-all]: UserAttribute extras contains no username for provider %q\", providerName)\n}\nuserAtProvider := usernames[0]\nfinalRedirectURL := authLogout.FinalRedirectURL\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- `fmt`: This is a standard Go library for formatted I/O.\n- `userAttributes`: This is a custom library that needs to be defined in the code.\n- `authLogout`: This is a custom library that needs to be defined in the code.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 Security Risks](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE for Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
