            {
              "id": "6445356b-ef6c-3eb5-8b3b-09521cbeb550",
              "name": "Potential Logic Bug Due to Reading Attribute Value from Two Different Sources",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Potential Logic Bug Due to Reading Attribute Value from Two Different Sources\" refers to a situation where a program reads an attribute value from two different sources. This can lead to inconsistencies and unexpected behavior if the two sources provide different values for the same attribute. In the Go programming language, this can occur when using the `mux.Vars(r)[\"provider\"]` and `r.URL.Query().Get(\"filter\")` methods to read the same attribute value from a URL's path and query string, respectively.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, ensure that each attribute value is read from a single, consistent source. If an attribute value needs to be read from multiple sources, implement a mechanism to handle any discrepancies between the different sources. This could involve prioritizing one source over the others, or throwing an error if the sources provide different values.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIn the provided code, the `provider` attribute is read from the URL's path using `mux.Vars(r)[\"provider\"]`, while the `filter` attribute is read from the URL's query string using `r.URL.Query().Get(\"filter\")`. If these two methods are intended to read the same attribute value, consider modifying the code to read the attribute value from a single source. For example:\n\n```go\nprovider := mux.Vars(r)[\"provider\"]\n\n// Parse pagination parameters.\npagination, err := parsePaginationParams(r)\nif err != nil {\n\twriteError(w, NewError(http.StatusBadRequest, err.Error()))\n\treturn\n}\n\n// Parse filter and excludedAttributes.\nvar filter *Filter\nvar excludeMembers bool\nif value := provider; value != \"\" {\n\tvar err error\n\tfilter, err = ParseFilter(value)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\twriteError(w, NewError(http.StatusBadRequest, err.Error()))\n\t\treturn\n\t}\n\t// Currently only support displayName eq \"<value>\" filter.\n\tif err := filter.ValidateForAttribute(\"displayName\", opEqual); err != nil {\n\t\twriteError(w, NewError(http.StatusBadRequest, err.Error()))\n\t\treturn\n\t}\n}\nif value := r.URL.Query().Get(\"excludedAttributes\"); value != \"\" {\n\tfields := strings.Split(value, \",\")\n\texcludeMembers = slices.Contains(fields, \"members\")\n}\n\nvar filterValue string\nif filter != nil {\n\tfilterValue = filter.Value\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `net/http` package from the Go standard library, for handling HTTP requests and responses.\n- The `github.com/gorilla/mux` package, for routing HTTP requests.\n- The `strings` package from the Go standard library, for manipulating strings.\n- The `slices` package, for working with slices.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)](https://cwe.mitre.org/index.html)"
