            {
              "id": "a8c275e1-774d-3d4e-bc2c-f291f79be041",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior and potential security vulnerabilities. This occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is shared across multiple iterations, leading to the same memory address being used for different iterations. This can lead to unexpected behavior as the value at that memory address can change in each iteration.\n\nIn the provided code, there is no direct evidence of this vulnerability. However, it's important to be aware of this issue when working with pointers in Go, especially within loops and goroutines.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it's recommended to avoid sharing pointers to loop variables across iterations. Instead, create a new variable within the scope of the loop body and use that instead. This ensures that each iteration has its own unique memory address, preventing unexpected behavior.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nAs mentioned, the provided code does not directly exhibit this vulnerability. However, if it did, the fix would involve creating a new variable within the loop body. For example:\n\n```go\nfor _, op := range payload.Operations {\n    op := op // create a new 'op' variable\n    // rest of the code...\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code appears to require the following libraries:\n\n- `logrus` for logging\n- `net/http` for HTTP status codes\n- `fmt` for formatting strings\n- `strings` for string manipulation\n\n## References\n\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE-476): NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)\n\nPlease note that the CWE link is not a perfect match for this vulnerability, but it's the closest match in terms of dealing with pointer-related issues."
              },
              "properties": {
