            {
              "id": "0c47ddb7-68b3-32bf-8dd9-0b3e4ab8f2f8",
              "name": "Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when the address of a loop iterator variable is shared among multiple goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines will see the same memory address and hence the same value (the last value of the loop variable). This can lead to race conditions and data inconsistency issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing the address of the loop iterator variable among multiple goroutines. Instead, you should pass the actual value of the loop variable to the goroutine or create a new variable within the scope of the loop and use that instead.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIn the provided code, there is no explicit sharing of loop iterator variable among multiple goroutines, so it doesn't seem to have the \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\". However, if there were, the fix would look something like this:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n    tt := tt // create a new 'tt' variable\n    t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        // rest of the code\n    })\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`\n- `net/http/httptest`\n- `github.com/gorilla/mux`\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/require`\n- `encoding/json`\n\n## References\n\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE-552)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/552.html)\n\nPlease note that the provided links are active and accessible for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
