            {
              "id": "a4776542-6e1a-30dd-bb13-cdfc445cb66b",
              "name": "Multiple Source Variable Assignment Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "The \"Multiple Source Variable Assignment Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a type of vulnerability where a variable can be assigned values from multiple sources. This can lead to unexpected behavior if the sources are not properly validated or sanitized. In the provided code, the variable `err` is assigned values from multiple sources, which could potentially lead to this vulnerability.\n\nMitigation Advice:\n- Always validate and sanitize input from all sources.\n- Avoid using the same variable to store values from different sources.\n- Handle errors properly to prevent unexpected behavior.\n\nSource Code Fix Recommendation:\nIn the provided code, the variable `err` is assigned values from multiple sources. To fix this, you can use different variables for each source. Here is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nerr1 := json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&payload)\nif err1 != nil {\n\t// handle error\n}\n\nlist, err2 := s.userCache.List(labels.Everything())\nif err2 != nil {\n\t// handle error\n}\n\nfor _, user := range list {\n\tattr, err3 := s.userAttributeCache.Get(user.Name)\n\tif err3 != nil {\n\t\t// handle error\n\t}\n}\n\nuser, err4 := s.userMGR.EnsureUser(principalName, payload.UserName)\nif err4 != nil {\n\t// handle error\n}\n\nerr5 := s.userMGR.UserAttributeCreateOrUpdate(user.Name, provider, groupPrincipals, extras)\nif err5 != nil {\n\t// handle error\n}\n```\n\nLibrary Dependencies:\n- `logrus` for logging\n- `net/http` for handling HTTP requests and responses\n- `strings` for string manipulation\n- `fmt` for formatting strings\n- `json` for handling JSON data\n\nOWASP Resources:\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n\nCommon Weakness Enumeration (CWE):\n- [CWE-20: Improper Input Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
