            {
              "id": "39121b11-d519-3ad3-b654-9b6149a57f46",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" is a common vulnerability in Go programming language where the developer unintentionally shares a pointer to a loop variable in goroutines or closures. This can lead to unexpected behavior as all goroutines or closures might end up using the same variable instance, which is the one corresponding to the last iteration of the loop.\n\nIn the provided code, the vulnerability does not seem to be present as there is no pointer sharing in the loop. However, if there were any goroutines or closures inside the loop that used the loop variable `tt`, it could potentially lead to this vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables in goroutines or closures. Instead, you should pass the loop variable as an argument to the goroutine or closure, or create a new variable inside the loop that takes the value of the loop variable and use that in the goroutine or closure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nAs mentioned, the provided code does not seem to have this vulnerability. However, if there were a goroutine or closure using the loop variable `tt`, a fix could look like this:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n\ttt := tt // create a new variable that takes the value of the loop variable\n\tt.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n\t\t// rest of the code\n\t})\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example seems to require the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`\n- `net/http/httptest`\n- `github.com/gorilla/mux`\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/require`\n- `encoding/json`\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-118: Incorrect Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n\nPlease note that the CWE link does not directly correspond to the vulnerability in question, but it is the closest match available in the CWE database."
