            {
              "id": "b3792ce1-ddfc-34d6-907e-ca8001d824f4",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation\" is a vulnerability that can occur in Go programming language when a pointer to a variable is unintentionally shared across goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior and potential data races, as the variable can be modified by one goroutine while it is being read by another.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability does not seem to be present as there is no concurrent execution or goroutines involved. However, if the loop was executed in a goroutine, and the `group` variable was a pointer, then the vulnerability could potentially occur.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid sharing pointers across goroutines. Instead, pass the actual value to the goroutine or create a new variable within the scope of the goroutine.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIf the loop was executed in a goroutine, the fix would look like this:\n\n```go\nfor _, group := range userInfo.GetGroups() {\n    localGroup := group\n    go func() {\n        req.Header.Add(\"Impersonate-Group\", localGroup)\n    }()\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we create a new variable `localGroup` within the scope of the loop, which gets its own copy of `group`'s value. This way, each goroutine has its own copy of the group value and there is no shared pointer.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet seems to be using the `net/http` package for handling HTTP requests. The `userInfo.GetGroups()` function is not a standard Go function and seems to be part of a custom `userInfo` type. Therefore, the dependencies would be:\n\n- `net/http`\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [CWE-118: Improper Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n\nPlease note that the CWE link provided is the closest match found for the described vulnerability, as there is no specific CWE for \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation\"."
