            {
              "id": "fca81d0d-e946-38ff-b23a-e979fac50462",
              "name": "Potential Logic Bug: Variable Assignment from Multiple Sources",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Potential Logic Bug: Variable Assignment from Multiple Sources\" in Go programming language refers to a situation where a variable is assigned values from multiple sources. This can lead to unpredictable behavior and potential security risks if not handled properly. In the provided code, the variables `tokenName` and `tokenKey` are assigned values from two different sources: `tokens.SplitTokenParts(tokenAuthValue)` and `token.Name, token.Token`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to ensure that variables are assigned values from a single, trusted source. If a variable must be assigned from multiple sources, ensure that the logic of the program handles these assignments in a predictable and secure manner. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIn the provided code, a possible fix would be to separate the logic for handling `tokenName` and `tokenKey` when they are empty and when they are not. This can be done by creating separate functions for each case.\n\n```go\nif tokenName == \"\" || tokenKey == \"\" {\n\thandleEmptyTokenNameAndKey()\n} else {\n\thandleNonEmptyTokenNameAndKey()\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to depend on the following libraries:\n\n- `logrus`: A structured logger for Go.\n- `apiv3`: A library for handling API version 3.\n- `features`: A library for handling feature flags.\n- `tokens`: A library for handling tokens.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A6 - Security Misconfiguration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-706: Use of Incorrectly-Resolved Name or Reference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/706.html)"
              },
