            {
              "id": "8b7b250e-adb1-3792-97b1-0377ec49de7d",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a developer uses a pointer to an iteration variable inside a goroutine. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines share the same instance of the variable. In the provided code, the `test` variable is shared across multiple goroutines, which can lead to race conditions and unexpected results.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop iteration variables across goroutines. Instead, you should pass the actual value to the goroutine or create a new variable for each iteration.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nfor _, test := range tests {\n    test := test // create a new 'test' variable\n    t.Run(test.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        hasher := Sha3Hasher{}\n        err := hasher.VerifyHash(test.hash, test.secretKey)\n        if test.wantError {\n            require.Error(t, err)\n        } else {\n            require.NoError(t, err)\n        }\n    })\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `testing`: standard library for testing go code.\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/require`: a third-party library for making assertions in tests.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
