            {
              "id": "f9551785-dadd-39bc-9149-a24b61caf70d",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" vulnerability refers to the situation where a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` field of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `isSecure`, which might be `false` depending on the context. If `Secure` is `false`, the cookie can be transmitted over unsecured HTTP connections, which makes it vulnerable to interception and misuse.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` field of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which provides the necessary security to prevent interception.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     CookieName,\n\tValue:    token.ObjectMeta.Name + \":\" + unhashedTokenKey,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
