            {
              "id": "a6d84b74-e63f-3a58-bbe6-074c8092fd7d",
              "name": "Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when the address of a loop iterator variable is shared among multiple goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines will see the same memory address and hence the same value (the last value of the loop variable). This can lead to race conditions and data inconsistency issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing the address of the loop iterator variable among multiple goroutines. Instead, you should pass the actual value to the goroutine or create a new variable within the scope of the loop and use its address.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n    tt := tt // Fix: create a new variable within the scope of the loop\n    t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        ctrl := gomock.NewController(t)\n        capiCache := fake.NewMockCacheInterface[*capi.Cluster](ctrl)\n        capiCache.EXPECT().Get(gomock.Any(), gomock.Any()).Return(tt.expected, tt.expectedErr).MaxTimes(1)\n        cluster, err := GetOwnerCAPICluster(tt.obj, capiCache)\n        if err == nil {\n            assert.Nil(t, tt.expectedErr)\n        } else if tt.expectedErr != nil {\n            assert.Equal(t, tt.expectedErr.Error(), err.Error())\n        } else {\n            assert.Fail(t, \"expected err to be nil, was actually %s\", err)\n        }\n        assert.Equal(t, tt.expected, cluster)\n    })\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `github.com/golang/mock/gomock`\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`\n- `testing`\n- `capi` (this seems to be a custom package, not a standard library)\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-362",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-362"
                ]
              }
