            {
              "id": "1552b6aa-33a6-3aa4-92eb-ee969855d038",
              "name": "Potential Logic Bug Due to Variable URL Assignment from Two Different Sources",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential logic bug due to variable URL assignment from two different sources. This vulnerability arises when the `url` and `pem` variables are assigned from two different sources (`settings.ServerURL.Get()` and `settings.CACerts.Get()`) without proper validation or sanitization. This could lead to unexpected behavior or security issues, such as unauthorized access or information disclosure, if the values of these variables are manipulated by an attacker.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to validate and sanitize the values of the `url` and `pem` variables before using them. This can be done by implementing input validation checks to ensure that the values of these variables are in the expected format and do not contain any malicious data. Additionally, it is also recommended to use secure coding practices and to follow the principle of least privilege, which means that a process should only have the minimum privileges necessary to perform its function.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```go\nurl, pem := settings.ServerURL.Get(), settings.CACerts.Get()\nif strings.TrimSpace(pem) != \"\" {\n\tca = []byte(pem)\n}\n\nif url == \"\" {\n\tpem = settings.InternalCACerts.Get()\n\turl = fmt.Sprintf(\"https://%s\", req.Host)\n\tif strings.TrimSpace(pem) != \"\" {\n\t\tca = []byte(pem)\n\t}\n} else if v, ok := req.Context().Value(tls.InternalAPI).(bool); ok && v {\n\tpem = settings.InternalCACerts.Get()\n\tif strings.TrimSpace(pem) != \"\" {\n\t\tca = []byte(pem)\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet provided requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- `fmt`\n- `strings`\n- `tls`\n- `settings`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A1 Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n- [CWE-20: Improper Input Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-20",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-20"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "75071df0-8b70-33cd-a187-2ca1edaf0ce3",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping: Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping: Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerability\" in Go programming language refers to a situation where an application directly writes user input into HTML responses without properly escaping it. This can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks, where an attacker can inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always escape user input before including it in an HTML response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes user input when rendering templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the JSON content to the response writer, you should use the `json.Encoder` to encode the JSON content and then write it to the response writer. This ensures that the JSON content is properly escaped.\n\nHere is a code example:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"encoding/json\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(rw http.ResponseWriter, req *http.Request) {\n    // Assume jsonContent is your JSON content\n    encoder := json.NewEncoder(rw)\n    err := encoder.Encode(jsonContent)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(rw, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `encoding/json`: This is a standard library in Go for encoding and decoding JSON data.\n- `net/http`: This is a standard library in Go for building HTTP servers and clients.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "12aa37e3-0538-32a5-8629-db94f7386232",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping: Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping: Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerability\" in Go programming language refers to a situation where an application directly writes user input into HTML responses without properly escaping it. This can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks, where an attacker can inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always escape user input before including it in an HTML response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes user input when rendering templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the JSON content to the response writer, you should use the `json.Encoder` to encode the JSON content and then write it to the response writer. This ensures that the JSON content is properly escaped.\n\nHere is a code example:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"encoding/json\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(rw http.ResponseWriter, req *http.Request) {\n    // Assume jsonContent is your JSON content\n    encoder := json.NewEncoder(rw)\n    err := encoder.Encode(jsonContent)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(rw, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `encoding/json`: This is a standard library in Go for encoding and decoding JSON data.\n- `net/http`: This is a standard library in Go for building HTTP servers and clients.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
