            {
              "id": "67e15dc0-c9ba-3eb3-9daf-6be0f718a252",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detection in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()' Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, this function does not perform any HTML escaping, which can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities if the content written to the response contains untrusted user input. XSS attacks occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always escape untrusted user input before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data inserted into HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the content to the response, you should use an HTML template to safely insert the content. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"content\").Parse(\"<div>{{.}}</div>\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(rw, content)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `{{.}}` placeholder in the template is automatically replaced with the `content` variable, and any special HTML characters in `content` are escaped to prevent XSS attacks.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "91f1e1d6-7da5-36d4-ac03-7533b1e8876d",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is shared among multiple goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines will see the same value - the one of the last iteration. This is due to the fact that the loop variable is reused in each iteration and the goroutines likely run after the loop has finished.\n\nIn the provided code, the issue might occur if the `updateConfigWithAdvertiseAddresses` function or the `assert` functions launch goroutines that use the `config` variable.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to the loop variable across multiple goroutines. Instead, you should create a new variable within the scope of the loop and use that in your goroutines.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n\tt.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n\t\tconfig := tt.initialConfig\n\t\tupdateConfigWithAdvertiseAddresses(config, tt.info)\n\t\t_, ok := config[\"advertise-address\"]\n\t\tif tt.expectAddrSet {\n\t\t\tassert.True(t, ok, \"expected advertise-address to be set\")\n\t\t\texpectedTlsSan, ok := tt.expectedConfig[\"tls-san\"]\n\t\t\tif ok {\n\t\t\t\tassert.ElementsMatch(t, expectedTlsSan, config[\"tls-san\"])\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\tassert.Equal(t, tt.expectedConfig[\"advertise-address\"], config[\"advertise-address\"])\n\t\t} else {\n\t\t\tassert.False(t, ok, \"expected advertise-address not to be set\")\n\t\t\tassert.Equal(t, len(tt.expectedConfig), len(config))\n\t\t}\n\t})\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `testing`: Standard Go library for testing.\n- `assert`: A third-party library for assertions in tests. It can be included by importing `\"github.com/stretchr/testify/assert\"`.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-118: Incorrect Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n\nPlease note that the links were active and accessible at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-118",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-118"
