            {
              "id": "0733a725-86c1-3192-ba23-ca9ee466e147",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is shared across multiple goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines will see the same memory location and hence the same value (the value of the last iteration). In the provided code, the issue arises when `tt` is used inside the goroutine created by `t.Run`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables across goroutines. Instead, you should pass the loop variable as an argument to the function that is creating the goroutine. This will ensure that each goroutine has its own copy of the variable.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n\ttt := tt // create a new 'tt' variable\n\tt.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n\t\tresult := removeReconciledCondition(tt.machine)\n\n\t\tif tt.machine == nil {\n\t\t\tassert.Nil(t, result)\n\t\t\treturn\n\t\t}\n\n\t\tassert.Equal(t, tt.expectedV1Beta2Conds, result.Status.Conditions)\n\t\tassert.Equal(t, tt.expectedV1Beta1Conds, result.GetV1Beta1Conditions())\n\t})\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to be using the `testing` package from the standard library and the `assert` package from the `testify` library. So, the dependencies are:\n\n- Standard library's `testing` package\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-118: Improper Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
