              "id": "fd538a91-8072-3885-ba24-0e8a27750bad",
              "name": "Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rate; Recommendation for Storage in CDN or Cloud Buckets",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rate; Recommendation for Storage in CDN or Cloud Buckets\" in Go programming language is related to the improper handling of unreadable files during security scans. This can lead to a high rate of false positives, which can mask real security threats and vulnerabilities. The vulnerability can be exploited by an attacker to bypass security measures and gain unauthorized access to sensitive data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n- Ensure that all files are readable and accessible during security scans.\n- Implement proper error handling to deal with unreadable files.\n- Regularly update and patch your Go programming language to the latest version.\n- Store sensitive data in secure storage solutions such as CDN or Cloud Buckets.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code is the decoding of a base64 string. The error handling for this operation is not properly implemented. Here is a recommended fix:\n\n```go\nperiodicOutputIPv6, err := base64.StdEncoding.DecodeString(\"\")\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatal(\"Error decoding base64 string: \", err)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `encoding/base64`\n- `log`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)](https://cwe.mitre.org/index.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL"
              }
