            {
              "id": "c8c0dbf5-409b-3929-933e-987bd45c476f",
              "name": "\"Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rates\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rates\" in Go programming language refers to the situation where the scanning process of a program excludes unreadable files, leading to high false positive rates. This can occur when the scanning process is unable to read certain files due to issues such as file permissions, resulting in these files being excluded from the scan. This can lead to a high number of false positives, as the scan may incorrectly identify these files as being safe when they may actually contain vulnerabilities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to ensure that all files are readable by the scanning process. This can be achieved by setting appropriate file permissions. Additionally, it is also recommended to use a scanning tool that is capable of handling unreadable files, rather than simply excluding them from the scan.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code snippet is a base64 encoded string, which is being decoded. The vulnerability does not seem to be directly related to this code snippet. However, if the decoded data is being used in a way that it's causing the scanning process to fail, you might need to handle the error returned by the `DecodeString` function and take appropriate action.\n\n```go\nperiodicOutputIPv4, err := base64.StdEncoding.DecodeString(\"\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet uses the `encoding/base64` package from the standard library of Go. No additional library dependencies are required for the code to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)](https://cwe.mitre.org/index.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f61dec82-2ab1-328f-950d-be5f940d61e6",
              "name": "Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "The \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when the address of a loop iterator variable is shared among multiple goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines will see the same memory address and hence the same value (the last value of the loop variable). This can lead to data races and other concurrency issues.\n\nIn the provided code, there is no direct evidence of this vulnerability. However, if the `tt` variable was a pointer and was used in a goroutine within the loop, it would be susceptible to this vulnerability.\n\nGeneral Mitigation Advice:\n- Avoid sharing the address of the loop iterator variable across multiple goroutines.\n- Instead, pass the actual value to the goroutine or create a new variable within the loop scope and share its address.\n\nSource Code Fix Recommendation:\nIf the `tt` variable was a pointer and used in a goroutine, the fix would be:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n    tt := tt // create a new 'tt' variable\n    go func() {\n        // use 'tt' in the goroutine\n    }()\n}\n```\n\nLibrary Dependencies:\n- The code seems to be using the `testing` package from the standard library.\n- It also uses the `semver` package for semantic versioning, which is not part of the standard library.\n- The `reflect` package from the standard library is used for deep equality checks.\n- The `time` package from the standard library is used for time-related operations.\n- The `assert` package, which is not part of the standard library, is used for assertions in tests.\n\nOWASP Resources:\n- [OWASP Go Secure Coding Practices](https://owasp.org/www-pdf-archive/Go_Secure_Coding_Practices_Guide.pdf)\n\nCommon Weakness Enumeration (CWE):\n- [CWE-118: Incorrect Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
