            {
              "id": "10f02f3a-1a8d-3ba3-a981-d7f4efd32dd1",
              "name": "Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "The \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is shared across multiple goroutines. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all goroutines will see the same memory location and hence the same value (the value of the last iteration). This can lead to race conditions and other concurrency issues.\n\nIn the provided code, the issue might occur if the `tc` variable is used inside the goroutine created by `t.Run`. If `tc` is a pointer and is modified in the loop, all goroutines will see the latest value of `tc`, which might not be what is expected.\n\nMitigation advice:\n\n- Do not share loop variables across goroutines.\n- If you need to share data, create a new variable within the scope of the goroutine and pass the data to this new variable.\n\nSource code fix recommendation:\n\n```go\nfor _, tc := range testCases {\n    tc := tc // create a new 'tc' variable\n    t.Run(tc.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        // rest of the code\n    })\n}\n```\n\nThe code example seems to require the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http/httptest`\n- `testing`\n- `fmt`\n- `strings`\n- `time`\n- `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`\n- `github.com/deislabs/oras/pkg/auth`\n- `github.com/helm/helm/v3/pkg/oci`\n\nOWASP resources:\n\n- [OWASP Go Secure Coding Practices](https://owasp.org/www-pdf-archive/Go_Secure_Coding_Practices_Guide.pdf)\n\nCommon Weakness Enumeration (CWE):\n\n- [CWE-552: Files or Directories Accessible to External Parties](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/552.html)\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)"
