            {
              "id": "aaf82dcd-b308-302f-8e0e-184bed7ba119",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If this function is used to directly write user-controlled input or error messages, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the input will be executed by the browser.\n\nThis vulnerability is particularly dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input or error messages before writing them to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any HTML or JavaScript code.\n\nIn addition, you should also validate and sanitize all user input to ensure that it does not contain any malicious code. This can be done using a combination of white-listing (only allowing certain types of input) and black-listing (blocking certain types of input).\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the vulnerable code:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"error\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(err.Error())\nt.Execute(w, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, the `template.New()` function is used to create a new HTML template. The `template.Parse()` function is used to parse the error message, which automatically escapes any HTML or JavaScript code. The `template.Execute()` function is then used to write the escaped error message to the HTTP response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
