                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ec1665a6-1253-31c5-94c2-2cb44c6b7e21",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a pointer variable is used inside a loop and its address is passed to a function or method. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all iterations of the loop will share the same memory address, and hence the same value. This can lead to data races and other concurrency issues if the loop is running in a concurrent context (like in goroutines).\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using pointers in loops whenever possible. If you need to use a pointer, make sure to create a new variable inside the loop scope and use that instead. This will ensure that each iteration of the loop has its own unique memory address.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, c := range cases {\n\tt.Run(c.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n\t\th := setup(t, auditlogv1.LevelHeaders)\n\t\tinput := inject(t, c.input, c.name) // create a new variable inside the loop\n\n\t\t_, err := h.auditpolicy.Create(&input)\n\t\trequire.NoError(t, err)\n\n\t\tactual, err := h.OnChange(testHandlerFuncKey, &input)\n\t\tassert.NoError(t, err)\n\n\t\tassert.Equal(t, c.expected, actual.Status)\n\t})\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example seems to require the following libraries:\n\n- `testing`: standard library for testing in Go.\n- `auditlogv1`: a custom library for audit logging.\n- `require` and `assert` from the `github.com/stretchr/testify` package for assertions in tests.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-567: Unsynchronized Access to Shared Data in a Multithreaded Context](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/567.html)"
