            {
              "id": "e2022d92-8f81-3630-aea2-0cb2a4764c66",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Export Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior and potential security vulnerabilities. This occurs when a pointer to a loop variable is incorrectly shared between iterations, leading to all iterations operating on the same memory location. This can lead to data races and unexpected behavior, especially in concurrent code.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, there is no direct evidence of this vulnerability. However, if `hook` was a pointer and was used in a goroutine or passed to a function that stores it for later use, this could lead to the vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables. Instead, you should create a new variable within the loop scope and use that instead. This ensures that each iteration of the loop has its own unique copy of the variable, preventing data races and other unexpected behavior.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nAssuming `hook` is a pointer, the fixed code would look like this:\n\n```go\nfor _, hook := range drainOpts.PostDrainHooks {\n    hook := hook // Create a new variable within the loop scope\n    delete(secret.Annotations, hook.Annotation)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it appears to be using the built-in `map` type and `range` keyword from the Go standard library.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-562: Return of Stack Variable Address](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/562.html)\n\nPlease note that these links are subject to change and may not be accessible at all times. Always ensure to check the validity of the links before using them."
