            {
              "id": "f16610e2-d897-33c5-9414-a4050344827d",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a pointer variable is used inside a loop and its address is passed to a goroutine or deferred function. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all iterations of the loop might end up using the same variable, which is the one from the last iteration. This is due to the fact that goroutines and deferred functions only run when the surrounding function exits, which is after the loop has finished executing.\n\nIn the provided code, the variable `tt` is used inside a goroutine (the anonymous function passed to `t.Run`). If `tt.setup()` or `getter.GetGlobalValue(tt.key)` have side effects or if they run in separate goroutines, they might not work as expected.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, you should avoid using loop variables directly inside goroutines or deferred functions. Instead, you should pass the variable as an argument to the goroutine or deferred function. This ensures that each iteration of the loop uses its own unique variable.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n\ttt := tt // This line is added to create a new 'tt' variable for each iteration\n\tt.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n\t\ttt.setup()\n\t\tgetter := chart.RancherConfigGetter{configCache}\n\t\tgot, err := getter.GetGlobalValue(tt.key)\n\t\tif tt.wantErr {\n\t\t\tassert.Error(t, err, \"Expected test to error.\")\n\t\t\treturn\n\t\t}\n\t\tassert.NoError(t, err, \"failed to get priority class.\")\n\t\tassert.Equal(t, tt.want, got, \"Unexpected priorityClassName returned\")\n\t})\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to depend on the following libraries:\n\n- `testing`: a standard library in Go for testing go code.\n- `chart`: a custom library, possibly for handling chart configurations.\n- `assert`: a library for assertions, possibly `github.com/stretchr/testify/assert`.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-118: Incorrect Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)"
