            {
              "id": "cd7ea955-a512-377d-881b-8d82c0c54d66",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior. This vulnerability occurs when a pointer to a loop iteration variable is unintentionally shared across multiple iterations. In Go, the range clause works by copying the value of each item into a new variable for each iteration. If a pointer to this variable is stored or used, it will point to the same memory location, and hence the same value, in all iterations.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid storing pointers to the loop iteration variable. Instead, you should create a new variable within the loop body and store a pointer to that variable. This ensures that each iteration has its own unique memory location and value.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, a := range subresources {\n    aCopy := a\n    varargs = append(varargs, &aCopy)\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a new variable `aCopy` is created in each iteration, and a pointer to `aCopy` is stored instead of a pointer to `a`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE-567)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/567.html)"
