            {
              "id": "d4420b54-b1a5-3cf5-9d91-013056f069fe",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a developer uses a pointer to a loop variable inside a goroutine. This happens because the loop variable is reused for each iteration in the loop, so its address doesn't change. As a result, all goroutines share the same variable, which can lead to unexpected behavior and potential data races.\n\nIn the provided code, the issue arises in the `t.Run` function where `tt` is used inside a goroutine. Since `tt` is a loop variable, it is shared among all goroutines, which can lead to unexpected behavior.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using loop variables directly inside goroutines. Instead, you should pass the loop variable as an argument to the goroutine or assign it to a new variable inside the loop.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n    tt := tt // Fix: create a new 'tt' variable\n    t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        t.Parallel()\n        rbController := fake.NewMockControllerInterface[*rbacv1.RoleBinding, *rbacv1.RoleBindingList](ctrl)\n        if tt.setupController != nil {\n            tt.setupController(rbController)\n        }\n        if err := removeAuthV2Permissions(tt.obj, rbController); (err != nil) != tt.wantErr {\n            t.Errorf(\"removeAuthV2Permissions() error = %v, wantErr %v\", err, tt.wantErr)\n        }\n    })\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `testing`: Standard Go testing package.\n- `fake`: A mock library, the exact library is not specified in the provided code.\n- `rbacv1`: A Kubernetes RBAC API package, likely `k8s.io/api/rbac/v1`.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-362: Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html)"
