            {
              "id": "b96fc204-8761-35eb-919a-43350f3f193a",
              "name": "Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Shared Loop Pointer Export Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that can lead to unexpected behavior. This happens when a pointer to a loop variable is shared across multiple goroutines. The loop variable is reused for each iteration of the loop, so its address doesn't change. This means that all goroutines end up sharing the same variable, which can lead to race conditions and other concurrency issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables across goroutines. Instead, you should create a new variable for each goroutine. This ensures that each goroutine has its own copy of the variable, preventing race conditions and other concurrency issues.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\nfor _, obj := range existingCrtbs {\n    obj := obj // create a new 'obj' variable\n    mockIndexer.Add(obj)\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a new 'obj' variable is created for each iteration of the loop. This ensures that each call to `mockIndexer.Add()` operates on its own copy of 'obj', preventing the shared loop pointer export vulnerability.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet doesn't specify any library dependencies. However, the `mockIndexer.Add()` function suggests that the code might depend on a mock testing library, such as `github.com/golang/mock/gomock`.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-118: Improper Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n\nPlease note that these links are subject to change and may not be accessible in the future."
