            {
              "id": "5d43d3b2-f16a-3704-a0fe-06d45fafcd64",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Exportation Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake where the developer unintentionally shares a pointer to a loop variable. This happens when a pointer to the loop variable is passed to a function literal (closure) that is invoked in a goroutine. Since the loop variable is reused across iterations, the goroutine may see the variable in a state that was never intended by the developer.\n\nIn the provided code, the loop variable `tt` is captured by the function literal passed to `t.Run`. If `t.Run` were to invoke the function literal in a goroutine, it could lead to a data race if the loop were to proceed to the next iteration before the goroutine had a chance to read `tt`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, you should avoid sharing pointers to loop variables. Instead, you should create a new variable within the scope of the loop body and use that instead.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n    tt := tt // create a new 'tt' variable\n    t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        // ... rest of the code ...\n    })\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a new `tt` variable is created for each iteration of the loop. This ensures that each function literal gets its own, unshared version of the `tt` variable.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code appears to depend on the following libraries:\n\n- `testing`: a standard library in Go for testing Go packages.\n- `metav1`: a package from Kubernetes API machinery project, provides metadata for Kubernetes resources.\n- `rbacv1`: a package from Kubernetes API, provides types for RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) resources.\n- `status`: it's not clear from the provided code, but it seems to be a custom package for handling status.\n- `controllers` and `fake`: these seem to be custom packages, possibly for handling Kubernetes controllers and for testing, respectively.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-118: Incorrect Access of Indexable Resource ('Range Error')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/118.html)\n\nPlease note that the links were active and accessible at the time of writing this report."
