            {
              "id": "9e7820de-9245-37e9-accd-4327cfaae194",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Export in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Export in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake where a developer unintentionally shares a pointer to a loop iteration variable. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all iterations of the loop use the same instance of the variable, so the pointer will always point to the value of the last iteration.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the function `AddAggregationManagementFeatureLabel(rb)` might be storing the pointer to `rb` for later use. If that's the case, it will always point to the value of the last iteration, not the value at the time of the function call.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid storing pointers to the loop iteration variable. Instead, you can create a new variable within the loop scope and store a pointer to that variable.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nfor _, rb := range desiredRBs {\n    rbCopy := rb\n    AddAggregationManagementFeatureLabel(&rbCopy)\n}\n```\n\nIn this version, `rbCopy` is a new variable that gets created in each iteration of the loop. Therefore, each function call receives a pointer to a different variable, avoiding the vulnerability.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not indicate any specific library dependencies. The `AddAggregationManagementFeatureLabel` function and `desiredRBs` variable are not part of the standard Go library, so their definitions and dependencies are not known.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-126: Buffer Over-read](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/126.html)\n\nPlease note that the CWE link is a best guess based on the provided information. The exact CWE might be different based on the specifics of how the `AddAggregationManagementFeatureLabel` function is implemented."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
