            {
              "id": "d9a3eecf-0179-384c-8231-cbe71bd7fe70",
              "name": "Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unintentional Pointer Sharing in Loop Iterations Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a common mistake that occurs when a pointer variable is used inside a loop and its address is passed to a function or stored for later use. This can lead to unexpected behavior because all iterations of the loop end up sharing the same memory address, so changes made in one iteration can affect others.\n\nIn the provided code, the variable `tt` is a pointer that is used inside a loop. If the function `tt.setupCRBController(crbController)` or `c.deleteDownstreamClusterRoleBindings(tt.crtb, crbController)` modifies the data that `tt` points to, it could affect the behavior of other iterations.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo avoid this vulnerability, you should avoid storing the address of a loop variable or passing it to a function. Instead, you can create a new variable inside the loop and use that instead.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nfor i := range tests {\n    tt := tests[i]\n    t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n        ctrl := gomock.NewController(t)\n        crbController := fake.NewMockNonNamespacedControllerInterface[*rbacv1.ClusterRoleBinding, *rbacv1.ClusterRoleBindingList](ctrl)\n        if tt.setupCRBController != nil {\n            tt.setupCRBController(crbController)\n        }\n\n        c := &crtbHandler{\n            s: status.NewStatus(),\n        }\n\n        if err := c.deleteDownstreamClusterRoleBindings(tt.crtb, crbController); (err != nil) != tt.wantErr {\n            t.Errorf(\"crtbHandler.deleteBindings() error = %v, wantErr %v\", err, tt.wantErr)\n        }\n    })\n}\n```\n\nIn this version, `tt` is a new variable that is created for each iteration of the loop, so there is no risk of unintentional pointer sharing.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `github.com/golang/mock/gomock`\n- `github.com/rancher/types/apis/management.cattle.io/v3`\n- `k8s.io/api/rbac/v1`\n- `github.com/rancher/norman/status`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A3:2017-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-459: Incomplete Cleanup](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/459.html)"
              },
